-Moscow_Prime_Time.pdf#page=7 ''Moscow Prime Time: How the Soviet Union Built the Media Empire that Lost the Cultural Cold War'', page 48], [[Cornell University Press]], 2011</ref><ref name=\"routledge\"/>|group=n|name=GungaSoviet}} (US$8.92&nbsp;million,{{#tag:ref|0.9 [[Soviet ruble]]s per US dollar from 1961 to 1971<ref name=\"russia\"/>|group=n|name=RubleUSD6171}} {{INR}}42.5&nbsp;million)<ref group=\"n\" name=\"RupeeUSD\"/> in 1965 (US${{Inflation|US|8.92|1965}} million or {{INR}}4.57&nbsp;billion<ref name=\"exchange16\"/> in 2016)|group=n|name=Gunga}}\n|-\n| 19\n| ''[[PK (film)|PK]]''\n| 2014\n| [[UTV Motion Pictures]] <br/> Rajkumar Hirani Films\n| [[Rajkumar Hirani]]\n| [[Abhijat Joshi]] <br> [[Rajkumar Hirani]]\n| $53.4&nbsp;million\n| {{sort|04.20|}} {{INR}}4.2&nbsp;billion (US$65&nbsp;million)\n| <ref group=\"n\" name=\"PK\"/>\n|-\n| 20\n| ''[[Jagir (1984 film)|Jagir]]''\n| 1984\n| Pramod Films\n| [[Pramod Chakravorty]]\n| [[Sachin Bhowmick]]\n| {{US$|28.01 million|long=no}}\n| {{sort|04.10|}} {{INR|4.1 billion}} ({{US$|63 million}})\n| <ref group=\"n\" name=\"Jagir\"/>\n|-\n| 21\n| ''[[Ram Aur Shyam]]''\n| 1967\n| Vijaya International\n| [[Tapi Chanakya]]\n| Kaushal Bharati\n| $10.1&nbsp;million\n| {{sort|03.96|}} {{INR}}3.96&nbsp;billion (US${{Inflation|US|10.1|1972}} million)\n| {{#tag:ref|''Ram Aur Shyam'' in Soviet Union: 8.35 million [[Soviet ruble|SUR]]{{#tag:ref|33.4&nbsp;million Soviet tickets sold,<ref name=\"soviet\"/> average ticket price of 25 [[Soviet ruble|kopecks]]<ref name=\"moscow7\"/>|group=n}} (US$10.1&nbsp;million,<ref>{{cite web|title=Archive (0.83 rubles per dollar)|url=http://cbr.ru/currency_base/OldDataFiles/USD.xls|website=[[Central Bank of Russia]]|year=1972}}</ref> {{INR}}76.8&nbsp;million){{#tag:ref|7.6 Indian rupees per US dollar in 1972<ref name=\"sauder\"/>|group=n}} in 1972<ref name=\"soviet\"/> (equivalent to US${{Inflation|US|10.1|1972}} million or {{INR}}3.96&nbsp;billion in 2016)<ref name=\"exchange2016\"/>|group=n}}\n|