{"title_page": "Katie Chapman", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = Katie Chapman\n| image          = Katie Chapman.jpg\n| image_size     = \n| caption        = With Arsenal in May 2009\n| fullname       = Katie Sarah Chapman<ref name=FIFA>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifadata.com/document/FWWC/2015/pdf/FWWC_2015_SquadLists.pdf |title=FIFA Women's World Cup Canada 2015: List of players: England |publisher=FIFA |format=PDF |page=10 |date=6 July 2015 |accessdate=1 June 2019}}</ref>\n| birth_date     = {{Birth date and age|1982|6|15|df=y}}<ref name=FIFA/>\n| birth_place    = [[Bermondsey]], London, England\n| height         = {{convert|1.71|m|order=flip}}<ref name=FIFA/>\n| position       = [[Midfielder]]<ref name=FIFA/>\n| currentclub    = \n| clubnumber     = \n| youthyears1    = 1992\u20131996\n| youthclubs1    = [[Millwall Lionesses L.F.C.|Millwall Lionesses]]\n| caps1          =   \n| goals1         =\n| years1         = 1996\u20132000\n| clubs1         = [[Millwall Lionesses L.F.C.|Millwall Lionesses]]\n| years2         = 2000\u20132004 |clubs2 = [[Fulham L.F.C.|Fulham Ladies]]                |caps2 =    |goals2 =\n| years3         = 2004\u20132006 |clubs3 = [[Charlton Athletic L.F.C.|Charlton Athletic]] |caps3 =    |goals3 =\n| years4         = 2006\u20132010 |clubs4 = [[Arsenal W.F.C.|Arsenal Ladies]]              |caps4 = 58 |goals4 = 30\n| years5         = 2010      |clubs5 = [[Chicago Red Stars]]                          |caps5 = 21 |goals5 = 0\n| years6         = 2010\u20132013 |clubs6 = [[Arsenal W.F.C.|Arsenal Ladies]]              |caps6 = 37 |goals6 = 5\n| years7         = 2014\u20132018 |clubs7 = [[Chelsea L.F.C.|Chelsea Ladies]]              |caps7 = 61 |goals7 = 7\n| nationalyears1 = 2000\u20132016\n| nationalteam1 = [[England women's national football team|England]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 94\n| nationalgoals1 = 8\n| club-update       = 10:05, 7 July 2018 (UTC) (UTC)<ref name=\"swstats\">{{cite web|title=Katie Chapman|url=http://us.women.soccerway.com/players/katie-chapman/19365/|publisher=Soccer Way|accessdate=11 February 2018}}</ref>\n| ntupdate       = 10:05, 7 July 2018 (UTC)\n| medaltemplates = \n{{Medal|Sport|Women's [[Association football|football]]}}\n{{Medal|Country|{{fbw|ENG}}}}\n{{Medal|Competition|[[FIFA Women's World Cup]]}}\n{{Medal|Bronze|[[2015 FIFA Women's World Cup|2015 Canada]]|}}\n}}\n'''Katie Sarah Chapman''' (born 15 June 1982) is an English former [[Association football|footballer]] who last played for English [[FA WSL]] club [[Chelsea L.F.C.|Chelsea Ladies]] and was a member of the [[England women's national football team|England women's national team]]. She primarily played as a [[Defensive midfielder|central midfielder]], although she was also deployed in [[Defender (association football)#Centre back|central defence]] while playing for England. Chapman has been described as \"a physical player who handles a brunt of the dirty work in the middle of the pitch.\"<ref name=chicago/><ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/2977227.stm|title=Katie Chapman|publisher=BBC Sport|date=25 April 2003 |accessdate=1 April 2011}}</ref> Her playing ability, profile and influence have drawn comparisons to former [[England national football team|England]] captain [[David Beckham]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://football.guardian.co.uk/pictures/image/0,8556,-10104600971,00.html|title=Katie Chapman|publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]]|accessdate=1 April 2011|location=London}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-1212228/Meet-Englands-star-midfielder-mother-wont-lining-Croatia-tonight.html|title=Move over Beckham, meet England's other star midfielder... the mother-of-two set to make football history in Euro final|date=9 September 2009 |publisher=[[Daily Mail]]|accessdate=1 April 2011|location=London}}</ref>\n\nChapman began her football career playing at primary school in her hometown of [[Bermondsey]]. At ten years old, she joined leading women's club [[Millwall Lionesses L.F.C.|Millwall Lionesses]]. In the 1996\u201397 season, Chapman made her senior team debut at the age of&nbsp;14. She became a regular starter in the team and also participated in the 1997 [[FA Women's Premier League Cup]] and [[FA Women's Cup]] final wins. In the 1998\u201399 campaign, Chapman won [[The Football Association|FA]] Young Player of the Year award. Already a full England international, she left Millwall in 2000 to sign a professional contract with [[Fulham L.F.C.|Fulham]]. She played on the teams that won back-to-back promotions, as well as the 2001\u201302 Premier League Cup and [[2002 FA Women's Cup Final|2002 FA Women's Cup]]. In June 2001 Chapman was again named FA Young Player of the Year. After two years with [[Charlton Athletic L.F.C.|Charlton Athletic]] from 2004, Chapman joined [[Arsenal W.F.C.|Arsenal Ladies]] and reached prominence with the team in her first season, winning a domestic [[Treble (association football)|treble]] as well as the [[UEFA Women's Cup]]. She had missed significant sections of the 2002\u201303 and 2007\u201308 seasons through pregnancy, and spent a single season with American [[Women's Professional Soccer]] team [[Chicago Red Stars]] in 2010, before returning to Arsenal Ladies. After another pregnancy truncated her 2013 season, Chapman moved across London to sign for [[Chelsea L.F.C.|Chelsea Ladies]] in January 2014.\n\nChapman is a former [[England women's national football team|England]] U\u201318 captain. She made her senior international debut aged 17 years in May 2000 in a [[2001 UEFA Women's Championship qualification]] match against [[Switzerland women's national football team|Switzerland]]. The following month, she made her first start against [[Norway women's national football team|Norway]]. In March 2002 she netted her first senior international goal in a 4\u20131 [[2003 FIFA Women's World Cup qualification]] win in the [[Netherlands women's national football team|Netherlands]]. In her first spell with the national team, Chapman represented England at four major international tournaments; [[2001 UEFA Women's Championship|UEFA Euro 2001]], [[2005 UEFA Women's Championship|UEFA Euro 2005]], [[2007 FIFA Women's World Cup|2007 FIFA World Cup]] and [[2009 UEFA Women's Championship|UEFA Euro 2009]]. A two-time winner of the FA International Player of the Year in 2002 and 2010, Chapman took a break from the national team in March 2011 with a total of 82 caps and eight goals. She was recalled to the England squad in February 2014 by new manager [[Mark Sampson]] and helped them finish third at the [[2015 FIFA Women's World Cup|2015 FIFA World Cup]].\n\n==Club career==\n\n===Millwall===\nChapman joined [[Millwall Lionesses L.F.C.|Millwall Lionesses]] as a ten-year-old, and made her first team debut at 14 in 1996\u201397.<ref name=cwfc/> That season she helped the Lionesses win an [[FA Women's Cup]] and [[FA Women's Premier League Cup|Premier League Cup]] double.<ref name=euro>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/women/4605953.stm|title=England squad guide|publisher=BBC|date=3 June 2005|accessdate=29 March 2011}}</ref> [[Louise Waller|Lou Waller]], who scored Millwall's winning goal in the [[1997 FA Women's Cup Final|FA Women's Cup final victory]] over [[Barnet F.C. Ladies|Wembley]], had been Chapman's coach in the club's youth teams.<ref>{{cite news |title=Football: Lionesses bring pride to Millwall|work=[[The Independent]]|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football-lionesses-bring-pride-to-millwall-1259819.html|accessdate=24 May 2011|author=Mike Rowbottom|date=5 May 1997|location=London}}</ref> In 1998\u201399 Chapman was named Young Player of the Year in the first ever FA Women's Football Awards.<ref name=award>{{cite web |title=F.A. WOMEN'S FOOTBALL AWARDS SPONSORED BY AXA 1998/1999|work=PR Newswire|url=http://www.prnewswire.co.uk/cgi/news/release?id=52516|accessdate=28 December 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Fulham===\nIn June 2000 Chapman signed a contract with newly professional [[Fulham L.F.C.|Fulham]] to become one of the first full-time professional female players in England.<ref name=cwfc/> It was reported that Chapman was one of the most highly paid players in the team, on an annual salary of about \u00a320,000.<ref>{{cite web |title=Article: Striking Katie leads the FA glory girls to a golden future|work=The Evening Standard|author=Patrick Sawyer|url=https://www.questia.com/read/1G1-85499354|accessdate=30 March 2011|date=7 May 2002}}</ref> In her first season with The Cottagers Chapman won the [[South West Combination Women's Football League]], the third level of women's football, and was again named FA Young Player of the Year.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.fulhamweb.co.uk/news/Katie-Chapman-Young-player-of-the-year.aspx|title=Katie confident of return|publisher=Fulham FC|date=5 June 2001|accessdate=30 March 2011}}</ref> She also played in Fulham's 1\u20130 FA Women's Cup final defeat to [[Arsenal W.F.C.|Arsenal]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/3004925/Womens-Football-Hard-graft-pays-off-for-Arsenal-as-Banks-grabs-decider-to-dent-Fulhams-ambitions.html|title=Women's Football: Hard graft pays off for Arsenal as Banks grabs decider to dent Fulham's ambitions|publisher=The Telegraph|date=7 May 2001|accessdate=30 March 2011|author=Sam Wallace|location=London}}</ref>\n\nIn 2001\u201302 Chapman helped Fulham win the [[FA Women's Premier League Southern Division]] and promotion to the top flight. She also scored two goals in the 7\u20131 Premier League Cup final win over [[Birmingham City L.F.C.|Birmingham City]], after which Fulham's manager Gaute Haugenes claimed Chapman was good enough to play in any national side in the world.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thefa.com/TheFACup/FACompetitions/TheFAWomensPLCup/NewsandFeatures/2002/10970.aspx|title=Birmingham City 1\u20137 Fulham|publisher=TheFA.com|date=7 April 2002|accessdate=30 March 2011|author=Matthew Cook}}</ref> Chapman then scored the winning goal in the [[2002 FA Women's Cup Final|2\u20131 FA Women's Cup final victory]] over Doncaster Belles, a volley from 20&nbsp;yards.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/news-and-comment/fulham-too-professional-for-battling-belles-650449.html|title=\nFulham too professional for battling Belles|publisher=The Independent|author=Tony Leighton|accessdate=3 October 2010|date=7 May 2005|location=London}}</ref> In Conclusion to the 2001\u201302 season, Chapman went on to be awarded the Ladies Player of the Season,<ref>{{cite news|title=Chapman wins award|url=http://www.fulhamfc.com/news/2002/may/07/chapman-wins-award|publisher=Fulham Official Website|date=7 May 2002|accessdate=10 April 2014}}</ref> as well as, winning the Nationwide International Player of the Year award.<ref>{{cite news|title=Chapman wins award|url=http://www.fulhamfc.com/news/2002/may/27/chapman-wins-award|publisher=Fulham Official Website|date=27 May 2002|accessdate=10 April 2014}}</ref>\n\nChapman sat out most of the following season due to pregnancy, as Fulham won a treble of [[FA Women's Premier League National Division]], FA Women's Cup and Premier League Cup. She made the announcement during half-time of a match against [[Tranmere Rovers L.F.C.|Tranmere Rovers]], and was promptly substituted by Haugenes \u2013 who quipped that he was not permitted to have 12&nbsp;players on the pitch at once.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://jacksonville.com/tu-online/stories/091302/spo_10438363.html|title=\nSports Briefs|publisher=Jacksonville.com|accessdate=31 March 2011|date=13 September 2002}}</ref> When Chapman returned to action, in the [[FA Women's Community Shield]] in August 2003, Fulham were no longer a professional outfit.<ref name=Charlton>{{cite news|url=http://tickets.cafc.co.uk/newsview.ink?nid=20353&newstype=l|title=Charlton add Chapman to ranks|publisher=Charlton Athletic FC|author=Matt Wright|accessdate=30 March 2011|date=14 July 2004|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20110831043408/http://tickets.cafc.co.uk/newsview.ink?nid=20353&newstype=l|archivedate=31 August 2011}}</ref> She represented Fulham in that season's [[UEFA Women's Champions League|Uefa Women's Cup]] campaign.<ref name=uefa>{{cite news|url=http://www.uefa.com/womenschampionsleague/news/newsid=95230.html |title=Fulham fire on all cylinders|publisher=[[UEFA]].com |date=25 August 2003 |accessdate=5 February 2013}}</ref> In March 2004 Chapman played in Fulham's Premier League Cup final defeat to Charlton Athletic.<ref name=Charlton/>\n\n===Charlton Athletic===\nJuly 2004 saw Chapman depart Fulham to sign for Charlton,<ref name=Charlton/> making her debut in a 1\u20130 Community Shield win over Arsenal at [[Broadhall Way]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.womenssoccerscene.co.uk/womens-football-news-2004-2005/040812-0.htm|title=Charlton capture Community Shield|publisher=Women's Soccer Scene|date=12 August 2004|accessdate=31 May 2011}}</ref> She played in The Addicks' 3\u20130 defeat to Arsenal in the Premier League Cup final in March 2005.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablese/eng-wom05.html|title=\nEngland (Women) 2004/05|publisher=RSSSF.com|accessdate=30 March 2011|date=17 June 2006|author=David Shannon}}</ref> She then missed the conclusion of the 2004\u201305 season, including Charlton's FA Women's Cup win, with a broken hand sustained on international duty.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thefa.com/England/womens-seniors/News/2005/Katie_confident_ofreturn|title=Katie confident of return|publisher=TheFA.com|date=5 May 2005|accessdate=29 March 2011}}</ref> In March 2006 Chapman played in her third successive Premier League Cup final, as Charlton beat Arsenal 2\u20131.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/women/4776978.stm|title=Arsenal 1\u20132 Charlton Athletic|publisher=BBC Sport|author=Tony Leighton|date=5 March 2006|accessdate=31 March 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Arsenal===\nChapman signed for league champions Arsenal in July 2006.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thefa.com/Leagues/WomensPremierLeague/NewsAndFeatures/2006/Chapman_movesto_Gunners|title=Chapman now a Gunner|publisher=TheFA.com|date=19 July 2006|accessdate=31 March 2011}}</ref> She marked her Gunners debut with the opening goal in a 3\u20130 Community Shield win over [[Everton L.F.C.|Everton]] at [[Gresty Road]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.arsenal.com/match/report/0708comm-shield-arsenal-ladies-3-everton-0?tab=report|title=Comm Shield: Arsenal Ladies 3 Everton 0|publisher=Arsenal.com|date=2 August 2006|accessdate=31 March 2011|author=Chris Harris}}</ref> In Chapman's first season at the club, Arsenal claimed an unprecedented [[Tuples in association football|quadruple]], winning the FA Premier League Cup, FA Women's Cup, FA Women's Premier League and the UEFA Women's Cup.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thefa.com/England/womens-seniors/News/2007/AwardsPiece|title=A season of achievement|publisher=TheFA.com|date=23 May 2007|accessdate=31 March 2011}}</ref> Arsenal's assistant coach [[Emma Hayes]] described Chapman as \"a rock that makes everything around her better. She was the engine and heartbeat of the successful quadruple-winning team.\"<ref name=chicago>{{cite news|url=http://www.womensprosoccer.com/Home/chicago/news/press_releases/091202-chapman-signing.aspx|title=Red Stars Sign Arsenal's Katie Chapman|publisher=WomensProSoccer.com|date=2 December 2009|accessdate=31 March 2011|author=Charlie Corr|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100912120402/http://www.womensprosoccer.com/Home/chicago/news/press_releases/091202-chapman-signing.aspx|archivedate=12 September 2010}}</ref> Midway through the 2007\u201308 season, Chapman's second pregnancy ruled her out of the rest of the campaign.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/women/7229059.stm|title=Westwood earns England Women spot|publisher=BBC|date=5 February 2008|accessdate=31 March 2011}}</ref>\n\nDuring 2008\u201309 Chapman returned to help Arsenal retain the league title; she also scored the opening goal in the 2009 FA Women's Cup final at [[Pride Park Stadium|Pride Park]] against [[Sunderland A.F.C. Women|Sunderland Ladies]], in a game which ended 2\u20131 to Arsenal.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2009/may/04/womens-fa-cup-final-arsenal-sunderland|title=Arsenal give Vic Akers the right send-off with the wrong performance|publisher=The Guardian|author=Tony Leighton|date=4 May 2009|accessdate=4 June 2010|location=London}}</ref> She had also featured in Arsenal's 5\u20130 Premier League Cup final win over Doncaster Rovers Belles.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thefa.com/TheFACup/FACompetitions/TheFAWomensPLCup/NewsandFeatures/2009/Arsenal_lift_the_cup|title=Arsenal lift The Cup|author=Glenn Lavery|publisher=TheFA.com|date=26 February 2009|accessdate=31 March 2011}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Katie Chapman 2014 (cropped).jpg|thumb|left|Captaining Chelsea in July 2014]]\n\n===Chicago Red Stars===\nIn December 2009 [[Women's Professional Soccer|WPS]] club [[Chicago Red Stars]] signed Chapman,<ref name=chicago/> who cited the need for a new challenge.<ref name=cnj>{{cite news|publisher=Camden New Journal|title=Women's Football: Katie Chapman returns to Arsenal Ladies|url=http://www.camdennewjournal.com/sports/2010/nov/womens-football-katie-chapman-returns-arsenal-ladies|date=10 November 2010|author=Sarah Marsh|accessdate=30 May 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722022840/http://www.camdennewjournal.com/sports/2010/nov/womens-football-katie-chapman-returns-arsenal-ladies|archivedate=22 July 2011}}</ref> The Red Stars announced that Chapman would join the club in time for the [[2010 Women's Professional Soccer season|2010 WPS season]], joining up with former Arsenal coach Emma Hayes and England team-mate [[Karen Carney]].<ref>{{cite news|publisher=BBC Sport|title=England women's Katie Chapman joins Chicago Red Stars|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/women/8392094.stm|date=2 December 2009}}</ref> After making 21&nbsp;appearances during the campaign, Chapman negotiated a mutual release from her contract and returned to Arsenal.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=WomensProSoccer.com|title=Red Stars Mutually Release Chapman|url=http://www.womensprosoccer.com/Home/chicago/news/press_releases/101001-redstars-chapman.aspx|date=1 October 2010|accessdate=31 March 2011}}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> It was reported that Chapman's husband had difficulty finding employment in America, so she returned home for the sake of her family.<ref name=cnj/>\n\n===Back to Arsenal===\nChapman rejoined Arsenal in October 2010, with the club on domestic hiatus before the launch of the [[FA WSL]]. She was praised by manager Laura Harvey after scoring late, decisive goals against [[Rayo Vallecano Femenino]] and [[Link\u00f6pings FC]] which helped to take Arsenal through to a [[UEFA Women's Champions League]] semi-final against eventual winners [[Olympique Lyonnais (Ladies)|Lyon]].<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Arsenal.com|title=Harvey \u2013 Chapman has had a major impact|url=http://www.arsenal.com/news/ladies-news/harvey-chapman-has-had-a-major-impact|date=25 March 2011|accessdate=24 May 2011|author=Chris Harris|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111020154026/http://www.arsenal.com/news/ladies-news/harvey-chapman-has-had-a-major-impact|archivedate=20 October 2011}}</ref> In May 2011, following injuries to [[Faye White]] and [[Jayne Ludlow]], Chapman [[Captain (association football)|captained]] the Arsenal team which beat [[Bristol Academy W.F.C.|Bristol Academy]] 2\u20130 at the [[Ricoh Arena]] to reclaim the FA Women's Cup.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=TheFA.com|title=Chapman's pride|url=http://www.thefa.com/TheFACup/FACompetitions/TheFAWomensCup/2010-11/TheFinal/Arsenal-BristolAcademy/Post-Match/Katie-Chapman|date=22 May 2011|accessdate=24 May 2011|author=Glenn Lavery}}</ref>\n\nArsenal and Chapman won the first two editions of the FA WSL in [[2011 FA WSL|2011]] and [[2012 FA WSL|2012]]. In March 2013 Arsenal announced that Chapman was seven months pregnant and would miss the first half of the [[2013 FA WSL|2013]] campaign.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]]|title=Congratulations Katie Chapman|url=http://www.arsenal.com/news/news-archive/congratulations-katie-chapman|date=19 March 2013|accessdate=1 June 2013}}</ref> She returned to the team in a friendly win over [[Coventry City L.F.C.|Coventry City]] in July 2013, following the birth of her third son.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]]|title=Coventry Ladies 0\u20134 Arsenal Ladies|url=http://www.arsenal.com/match/report/1314/post/ladies/coventry-ladies-0-4-arsenal-ladies|date=24 July 2013|accessdate=8 September 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 August 2013, Chapman made a substitute appearance in Arsenal's 3\u20130 FA WSL win over [[Liverpool L.F.C.|Liverpool]]. The FA decreed she had not been properly registered and Arsenal were deducted three points. The blunder meant that Arsenal \u2013 champions for the last nine consecutive seasons \u2013 could not finish higher than third and would not qualify for the 2014\u201315 UEFA Women's Champions League, unless they won the 2013\u201314 competition.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[British Broadcasting Corporation]]|title=Arsenal Ladies: FA deducts points after Chapman sub appearance|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/24115826|date=16 September 2013|accessdate=21 September 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Chelsea===\nIn January 2014, Chelsea announced the double [[Transfer (association football)|transfer]] of Chapman and [[Gilly Flaherty]] from Arsenal. The move reunited Chapman with Emma Hayes, her coach from Arsenal and Chicago. She hoped that training more regularly with Chelsea would kick start her international career.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[British Broadcasting Corporation]]|title=Katie Chapman has England hopes after sealing Chelsea switch|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/25667416|date=9 January 2014|accessdate=9 January 2014|first=Alistair|last=Magowan}}</ref> In August 2015 Chapman captained Chelsea in their FA Women's Cup [[2015 FA Women's Cup Final|final]] against [[Notts County L.F.C.|Notts County]], the first time the event had been staged at [[Wembley Stadium]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Chapman|first1=Katie|title=Women's FA Cup: Katie Chapman's road to Wembley|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/get-inspired/33689594|accessdate=1 August 2015|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|date=29 July 2015}}</ref> She described the experience as \"overwhelming\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Women's FA Cup final is 'great history' \u2013 Chelsea's Katie Chapman|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/33738883|accessdate=1 August 2015|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|date=31 July 2015}}</ref> Chelsea's 1\u20130 win before a Cup final record 30,710 crowd secured the club's first major trophy. It was the ninth FA Women's Cup winner's medal of Chapman's career.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Garry|first1=Tom|title=Women's FA Cup final: Chelsea Ladies 1\u20130 Notts County Ladies|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/33541364|accessdate=1 August 2015|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|date=1 August 2015}}</ref> In October 2015 she played in Chelsea's 4\u20130 win over Sunderland which secured the club's first [[FA WSL]] title and a League and Cup \"[[Double (association football)|double]]\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Garry|first1=Tom|title=WSL 1: Chelsea Ladies 4\u20130 Sunderland Ladies|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/34372478|accessdate=8 October 2015|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|date=4 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[2018 FA Women's Cup Final]], Chapman secured a record 10th winner's medal as Chelsea beat Arsenal 3\u20131 at Wembley.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Garry |first1=Tom |title=Katie Chapman: Record 10th Women's FA Cup for Chelsea captain, but 'more to come' |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/44012506 |accessdate=7 July 2018 |publisher=[[BBC Sport]] |date=6 May 2018}}</ref> Five days later she announced that she was retiring from football at the end of the 2017\u201318 season.<ref>{{cite news |title=Katie Chapman: Chelsea Ladies captain & England midfielder to retire this summer |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/44074631 |accessdate=7 July 2018 |publisher=[[BBC Sport]] |date=10 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nAs a 16-year-old, Chapman was called into the [[England women's national football team|England]] U\u201318 team, and captained her country at that level.<ref name=cwfc/> Chapman made her senior debut for England at 17, during the [[2001 UEFA Women's Championship qualification]] tournament, replacing [[Samantha Britton]] after 73&nbsp;minutes of a 1\u20130 win over [[Switzerland women's national football team|Switzerland]] in [[Bristol]] on 6&nbsp;May 2000.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thefa.com/England/womens-seniors/News/2000/2613|title=Smith makes her mark|publisher=TheFA.com|date=7 May 2000|accessdate=29 March 2011}}</ref> Chapman's first senior start came in an 8\u20130 reverse to [[Norway women's national football team|Norway]] in June 2000. Despite the heavy defeat she was praised for her performance by national coach [[Hope Powell]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thefa.com/England/womens-seniors/News/2000/2628|title=Powell's hopes hit|publisher=TheFA.com|date=2 June 2000|accessdate=29 March 2011}}</ref> England qualified for the final tournament with Chapman named Player of the Match in the away leg of the play-off win over [[Ukraine women's national football team|Ukraine]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thefa.com/England/womens-seniors/News/2000/1036|title=Striking result takes England close|publisher=TheFA.com|date=2 October 2000|accessdate=29 March 2011}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[2001 UEFA Women's Championship]] finals, Chapman played in all three of England's games and was praised for her performances by [[UEFA]]<ref name=cwfc/> and the victorious German coach [[Tina Theune-Meyer]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thefa.com/England/womens-seniors/News/2001/2947|title=Dawn of a new era|publisher=TheFA.com|date=3 July 2001|accessdate=29 March 2011}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Katie Chapman (cropped).jpg|thumb|left|Training with England in 2015|upright]]\n\nIn March 2002 Chapman headed her first goal for England in a 4\u20131 [[2003 FIFA Women's World Cup qualification]] win in the [[Netherlands women's national football team|Netherlands]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2002/mar/25/newsstory.sport12?INTCMP=SRCH|title=England leave false impression of China task|publisher=The Guardian|date=25 March 2002|accessdate=30 March 2011|author=Paula Cocozza|location=London}}</ref> She was named FA International Player of the Year for 2002.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/2006341.stm|title=Spacey bags three awards|publisher=BBC|date=24 May 2002|accessdate=30 March 2011|author=Tony Leighton}}</ref> Without Chapman \u2013 pregnant with her first child \u2013 England eventually failed to reach the [[2003 FIFA Women's World Cup]] after a play-off defeat to [[France women's national football team|France]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thefa.com/England/womens-seniors/News/2002/27096|title=Chapman's China dreams|publisher=TheFA.com|date=15 October 2002|accessdate=29 March 2011}}</ref>\n\nDespite a hand injury, Chapman also played every minute of all three games<ref>{{cite news|url=https://tickets.cafc.co.uk/newsview.ink?nid=22282&newstype=l|title=Euro exit for Charlton trio|publisher=Charlton Athletic|accessdate=30 March 2011|date=12 June 2005|author=Matt Wright|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110831045135/https://tickets.cafc.co.uk/newsview.ink?nid=22282&newstype=l|archivedate=31 August 2011}}</ref> for England at the [[2005 UEFA Women's Championship]], now featuring in midfield as she did at club level.<ref name=euro/> Her initial appearances for the national team had come in central defence.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sportacademy/hi/sa/football/video_masterclasses/newsid_2125000/2125225.stm|title=No way past Katie Chapman|publisher=BBC|accessdate=30 March 2011|date=12 July 2002}}</ref> At the [[2007 FIFA Women's World Cup]] Chapman started three matches, missing the group game against [[Argentina women's national football team|Argentina]] after picking up her second booking of the tournament during an impressive performance against [[Germany women's national football team|Germany]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2007/sep/14/newsstory.sport?INTCMP=SRCH|title=Heroic England hold Germany at bay|publisher=The Guardian|date=14 September 2007|accessdate=30 March 2011|author=Anna Kessel|location=London}}</ref>\n\nOn Chapman's return to the team she scored two goals in a [[Cyprus Cup]] win over [[South Africa women's national football team|South Africa]] in March 2009. It was her first appearance for England since October 2007, due to the birth of her second child.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thefa.com/England/womens-seniors/News/2009/Chapmans_childs_play|title=Chapman's Childs Play|publisher=TheFA.com|date=7 March 2009|accessdate=29 March 2011}}</ref> In May 2009, Chapman was one of the first 17 female players to be given central contracts by [[The Football Association]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/women/8050189.stm|title=England Women awarded contracts|publisher=BBC Sport|date=14 May 2009|accessdate=29 July 2009}}</ref> She was an ever-present in midfield during England's run to the [[2009 UEFA Women's Championship]] final.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thefa.com/England/All-Teams/Players/C/Katie-Chapman|title=Katie Chapman|publisher=TheFA.com|accessdate=30 March 2011}}</ref> In 2010 Chapman was named FA International Player of the Year for the second time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefa.com/GetIntoFootball/Players/PlayersPages/WomensAndGirls/NewsandFeatures/2010/FAWFA10 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120919123655/http://www.thefa.com/GetIntoFootball/Players/PlayersPages/WomensAndGirls/NewsandFeatures/2010/FAWFA10 |url-status=dead |archive-date=19 September 2012 |title=Key figures honoured at Women's awards |publisher=TheFA.com |accessdate=5 September 2010 }}</ref>\n\nAhead of a March 2011 friendly against [[United States women's national soccer team|United States]], Chapman unexpectedly withdrew from the England squad and quit international football. The decision, related to Chapman's family commitments, was reported to have left England's [[2011 FIFA Women's World Cup|World Cup]] preparations in disarray.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/women/9439172.stm|title=England hit by Katie Chapman retirement|publisher=BBC Sport|date=28 March 2011|accessdate=29 March 2011|author=Tony Leighton}}</ref> Hope Powell praised Chapman as \"a wonderful servant to England over the years\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.uefa.com/womensworldcup/news/newsid=1613092.html|title=Chapman steps back from England team|publisher=[[UEFA]].com|date=29 March 2011|accessdate=29 March 2011}}</ref> Chapman later confirmed she had been unhappy about a perceived lack of support with childcare costs and arrangements while on international duty.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2012/oct/15/few-working-mums-in-sport|title=Why is there only one working mum in elite football?|publisher=[[The Guardian]]|date=15 October 2012|accessdate=8 September 2013|first=Carrie|last=Dunn}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2013/aug/22/hope-powell-england-players|title=Hope Powell's ruthless brilliance will not be missed by England's players|publisher=[[The Guardian]]|date=22 August 2013|accessdate=8 September 2013|first=Anna|last=Kessel}}</ref> At the 2011 World Cup, Powell stressed that the FA had tried hard to accommodate Chapman's requirements: \"Katie was away with us in 2009 when we paid for her family to come along but at the end of the day there is not a bottomless pit of money in the women's game.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.express.co.uk/sport/football/252169/Katie-Chapman-s-boys-mean-the-World-to-her|title=Katie Chapman's boys mean the World to her|publisher=[[Daily Express]]|date=12 June 2011|accessdate=8 September 2013|first=Colin|last=Mafham}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2013, after Powell had been sacked, Chapman gave an interview to [[BBC Radio 5 Live]] in which she lamented her treatment. Chapman recalled that she asked for time off to look after her children in a brief conversation with Powell, only to receive an e-mail cancelling her central contract three hours later. She clarified that she had never retired from international football and that she still wanted to return and win 100 caps.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[British Broadcasting Corporation]]|title=England's Katie Chapman queries FA stance on motherhood|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/24078769|date=14 September 2013|accessdate=21 September 2013}}</ref>\n\nPowell's successor [[Mark Sampson]] eventually recalled Champman to the national team squad in February 2015, for a friendly against the United States in [[Milton Keynes]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Katie Chapman recalled by England for USA friendly|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/31132685|accessdate=8 February 2015|publisher=[[British Broadcasting Corporation]]|date=4 February 2015}}</ref> In May 2015 Sampson confirmed Chapman in his final squad for the [[2015 FIFA Women's World Cup]], to be hosted in Canada.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lavery|first1=Glenn|title=England squad named for FIFA Women's World Cup|url=http://www.thefa.com/news/england/womens/2015/may/world-cup-canada-2015-squad-announcement|accessdate=28 May 2015|publisher=[[The Football Association]]|date=11 May 2015}}</ref> During the tournament Chapman celebrated her 33rd birthday and her husband and three sons flew out for a surprise visit.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Taylor|first1=Louise|title=England's Katie Chapman ready for mother of all battles against Canada|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2015/jun/25/england-katie-chapman-canada-womens-world-cup|accessdate=1 August 2015|publisher=[[The Guardian]]|date=25 June 2015}}</ref> Despite her selection she made further public criticisms of the FA's ongoing lack of childcare arrangements.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Magowan |first1=Alistair |title=Katie Chapman: England player says FA can still improve childcare |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/32699605 |accessdate=7 July 2018 |publisher=[[BBC Sport]] |date=11 May 2015}}</ref> England eventually finished in third place after Chapman, starting her fifth match of the tournament, helped them beat Germany 1\u20130 in the bronze medal play-off.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Wittenberg|first1=Daniel|title=Women's World Cup: England claim bronze|url=http://www.chelseafc.com/news/latest-news/2015/07/women_s-world-cup--england-claim-bronze.html|accessdate=1 August 2015|publisher=[[Chelsea F.C.]]|date=28 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nChapman's final appearance for England came in April 2016. In September 2017 she accused Sampson of leaving her out of the national team because she was getting divorced.<ref name=\"divorce\">{{cite news |title=Katie Chapman 'not picked for England since divorce' |url=http://sport.bt.com/football/katie-chapman-not-picked-for-england-since-divorce-S11364210993646 |accessdate=7 July 2018 |publisher=[[BT Sport]] |date=9 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n===International goals===\n:''Scores and results list England's goal tally first.''\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! # !! Date !! Venue !! Opponent !! Score !! Result !! Competition\n|-\n| 1. || 23 March 2002 || [[Zuiderpark Stadion]], [[The Hague]] || {{fbw|NED}} || '''1'''\u20130 || 4\u20131 || [[2003 FIFA Women's World Cup qualification (UEFA)#Group 4|2003 World Cup qualifier]]\n|-\n| 2. || 27 October 2005 || Tapolca Stadium, [[Tapolca]] || {{fbw|HUN}} || '''5'''\u20130 || 13\u20130 || [[2007 FIFA Women's World Cup qualification (UEFA)|2007 World Cup qualifier]]\n|-\n| 3. || 13 May 2007 || [[Priestfield Stadium]], [[Gillingham, Kent|Gillingham]] || {{fbw|NIR}} || '''3'''\u20130 || 4\u20130 || [[2009 UEFA Women's Championship qualification|Euro 2009 qualifier]]\n|-\n| 4. || rowspan=\"2\" | 17 May 2007 || rowspan=\"2\" | [[Roots Hall]], [[Southend-on-Sea]] || rowspan=\"2\" | {{fbw|ISL}} || '''2'''\u20130 || rowspan=\"2\" | 4\u20130 || rowspan=\"2\" | [[Exhibition game|Friendly]]\n|-\n| 5. || '''4'''\u20130\n|-\n| 6. || rowspan=\"2\" | 5 March 2009 || rowspan=\"2\" | [[GSZ Stadium]], [[Larnaca]] || rowspan=\"2\" | {{fbw|RSA}} || '''5'''\u20130 || rowspan=\"2\" | 6\u20130 || rowspan=\"2\" | [[2009 Cyprus Cup]]\n|-\n| 7. || '''6'''\u20130\n|-\n| 8. || 1 April 2010 || [[The Den|New Den]], [[London]] || {{fbw|ESP}} || '''1'''\u20130 || 1\u20130 || [[2011 FIFA Women's World Cup qualification \u2013 UEFA Group 5#England v Spain|2011 World Cup qualifier]]\n|}\n\n===Great Britain Olympic===\nIn June 2012 Chapman was not included in the final 18-player [[Great Britain women's Olympic football team|Great Britain]] squad for the [[Football at the 2012 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's tournament|2012 London Olympics]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/olympics/18592483|title=Team GB women's squad for London 2012 announced|publisher=BBC Sport|date=26 June 2012|accessdate=8 September 2013}}</ref> She had made the 35-player longlist but was hurt and disappointed to be overlooked for the event in her home city. Chapman felt that her decision to withdraw from the England squad had caused Hope Powell \u2013 who managed Great Britain as well as England \u2013 to leave her out.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://beamagazine.wordpress.com/2012/08/14/interview-arsenals-katie-chapman-talks-about-the-olympics-england-and-motherhood/|title=Interview: Arsenal's Katie Chapman talks about the Olympics, England, and motherhood|publisher=Bea Magazine|date=14 August 2012|accessdate=8 September 2013|last=Dunn|first=Carrie}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nChapman has three sons with former husband Mark Wilkinson, a [[construction worker]] she met while he coached at Millwall Lionesses.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Chaudhury |first1=Vivek |title=Footballers husbands |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/footballers-husbands-7270548.html |accessdate=7 July 2018 |publisher=[[London Evening Standard]] |date=3 June 2005}}</ref> During the pregnancies Chapman trained until two weeks before the birth, then resumed training six weeks afterwards.<ref name=koski>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/home/you/article-1362607/England-women-s-football-team-aiming-win-World-Cup.html|title=A whole different ball game: Meet the women aiming to win the World Cup\n|publisher=[[Daily Mail]]|date=11 March 2011|accessdate=29 March 2011|author=John Koski|location=London}}</ref> In 2002\u201303 Chapman sat out Fulham's treble winning season while pregnant with Harvey, but returned in August 2003 and played in the [[FA Women's Community Shield]] win over [[Doncaster Rovers Belles|Doncaster Belles]].<ref name=cwfc>{{cite web|url=http://www.freewebs.com/macacresswell4eva/englandwomen.htm |title=England women Fixtures and Results, 2004/05 |publisher=Cresswell Wanderers FC |accessdate=11 October 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121024012842/http://www.freewebs.com/macacresswell4eva/englandwomen.htm |archivedate=24 October 2012 }}</ref>\n\nAs of January 2008, Chapman announced she was pregnant with Riley, and as a result played no further part in Arsenal's 2007\u201308 season. Riley was born on 8&nbsp;July. Chapman returned to Arsenal for the 2008\u201309 season and assisted in their 5\u20131 victory over [[Nottingham Forest L.F.C.|Nottingham Forest Ladies]], in Carlton, on 18&nbsp;September.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.arsenal.com/match/report/0809/post/ladies/nottm-forest-v-arsenal-ladies?tab=report|title=Nottingham Forest 1 \u2013 5 Arsenal|publisher=Arsenal|date=18 September 2009|accessdate=29 March 2011}}</ref> She divorced Mark in 2016.<ref name=\"divorce\" />\n\nChapman is a lifelong supporter of [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]],<ref name=millwall>{{cite news|url=http://www.millwallfc.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10367~2056533,00.html|title=Three Lions on her shirt...|publisher=Millwall FC|date=21 May 2010|accessdate=29 March 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100530124120/http://www.millwallfc.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10367~2056533,00.html|archivedate=30 May 2010}}</ref> and has trained as a [[beautician]].<ref name=koski/> Katie has a twin, Sophie, who she played alongside at Millwall Lionesses.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content.espressoeducation.com/espresso/modules/t2_special_reports/sport/world_cup_2002/www_girls_football/girlsfootball/stars.html|title=Meet the Stars|publisher=[[The Football Association]]|accessdate=27 October 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130122233750/http://content.espressoeducation.com/espresso/modules/t2_special_reports/sport/world_cup_2002/www_girls_football/girlsfootball/stars.html|archivedate=22 January 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n[[File:Chelsea Ladies 1 Notts County Ladies 0 (20183103506) (2).jpg|thumb|right|Waiting to be interviewed on the pitch at Wembley Stadium, August 2015]]\n\n'''Millwall Lionesses'''\n*[[FA Women's Cup]]: 1996\u201397{{citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n*[[FA Women's Premier League Cup]]: 1996\u201397{{citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n\n'''Fulham'''\n*[[FA Women's Premier League National Division]]: 2002\u201303{{citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n*[[FA Women's Premier League Southern Division]]: 2001\u201302{{citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n*[[South East Combination Women's Football League]]: 2000\u201301{{citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n*FA Women's Cup: 2001\u201302, 2002\u201303{{citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n*FA Women's Premier League Cup: 2001\u201302, 2002\u201303{{citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n\n'''Charlton Athletic'''\n*FA Women's Cup: 2004\u201305{{citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n*FA Women's Premier League Cup: 2005\u201306{{citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n\n'''Arsenal'''\n*[[FA WSL]]: 2011, 2012{{citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n*FA Women's Premier League National Division: 2006\u201307, 2007\u201308, 2008\u201309{{citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n*[[UEFA Women's Champions League|UEFA Women's Cup]]: 2006\u201307{{citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n*FA Women's Cup: 2006\u201307, 2007\u201308, 2008\u201309, 2010\u201311{{citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n*FA Women's Premier League Cup: 2006\u201307, 2008\u201309{{citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n*[[FA WSL Continental Cup]]: 2011{{citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n*[[FA Women's Community Shield]]: 2006{{citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n\n'''Chelsea'''\n*FA WSL: 2015{{citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n*FA Women's Cup: 2014\u201315, 2017\u201318{{citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n\n'''England'''\n*[[Cyprus Cup]]: 2009, 2015{{citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n*[[UEFA Women's Championship]] runner-up: [[2009 UEFA Women's Championship|2009]]<ref>{{cite web |title=UEFA Women's EURO 2009 - Final |url=https://www.uefa.com/womenseuro/season=2009/matches/round=15050/match=2001423/postmatch/lineups/index.html |publisher=UEFA |accessdate=7 July 2019 |date=10 September 2009}}</ref>\n*[[FIFA Women's World Cup]] third place: [[2015 FIFA Women's World Cup|2015]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://resources.fifa.com/mm/document/tournament/competition/02/66/09/64/eng_51_0704_ger-eng_fulltime.pdf |date=4 July 2015 |title=Match for third place - Match report |publisher=FIFA |format=PDF |accessdate=7 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n'''Individual'''\n<!--LEAGUE AND FEDERATION-SANCTIONED AWARDS ONLY. No fan or magazine-voted awards. Listed in chronological order from last time won.-->\n*FA Women's Young Player of the Year: 1998\u201399, 2000\u201301{{citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n*FA Women's International Player of the Year: 2001\u201302, 2009\u201310{{citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*{{FIFA player}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110423152659/http://www.arsenal.com/ladies/players/katie-chapman Profile] at Arsenal.com\n*[http://www.thefa.com/England/All-Teams/Players/C/Katie-Chapman Katie Chapman] at the FA website\n*[https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http://www.geocities.com/titch2401/katiechapman.html&date=2009-10-25+23:07:34  Unofficial website]\n\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Awards\n| bg = Gold\n| bordercolor = #000000\n| list1 = \n{{FA Women's Young Player of the Year}}\n{{FA Women's International Player of the Year}}\n}}\n{{Navboxes\n| title = England squads\n| bg = white\n| fg = #CF081F\n| bordercolor = #0B0B3F\n| list1 = \n{{England squad 2001 UEFA Women's European Championship}}\n{{England squad 2005 UEFA Women's European Championship}}\n{{England squad 2007 FIFA Women's World Cup}}\n{{England squad 2009 UEFA Women's European Championship}}\n{{England squad 2015 FIFA Women's World Cup}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chapman, Katie}}\n[[Category:1982 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Bermondsey]]\n[[Category:English women's footballers]]\n[[Category:England women's international footballers]]\n[[Category:Arsenal W.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Chelsea F.C. Women players]]\n[[Category:Millwall Lionesses L.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Fulham L.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Charlton Athletic W.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:FA Women's National League players]]\n[[Category:Chicago Red Stars (WPS) players]]\n[[Category:Expatriate women's soccer players in the United States]]\n[[Category:English expatriate sportspeople in the United States]]\n[[Category:FA Women's Super League players]]\n[[Category:English expatriate women's footballers]]\n[[Category:2007 FIFA Women's World Cup players]]\n[[Category:2015 FIFA Women's World Cup players]]\n[[Category:Women's association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Twin sportspeople]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = Katie Chapman\n| image          = Katie Chapman.jpg\n| image_size     = \n| caption        = With Arsenal in May 2009\n| fullname       = Katie Sarah Chapman<ref name=FIFA>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifadata.com/document/FWWC/2015/pdf/FWWC_2015_SquadLists.pdf |title=FIFA Women's World Cup Canada 2015: List of players: England |publisher=FIFA |format=PDF |page=10 |date=6 July 2015 |accessdate=1 June 2019}}</ref>\n| birth_date     = {{Birth date and age|1982|6|15|df=y}}<ref name=FIFA/>\n| birth_place    = [[Bermondsey]], London, England\n| height         = {{convert|1.71|m|order=flip}}<ref name=FIFA/>\n| position       = [[Midfielder]]<ref name=FIFA/>\n| currentclub    = \n| clubnumber     = \n| youthyears1    = 1992\u20131996\n| youthclubs1    = [[Millwall Lionesses L.F.C.|Millwall Lionesses]]\n| caps1          =   \n| goals1         =\n| years1         = 1996\u20132000\n| clubs1         = [[Millwall Lionesses L.F.C.|Millwall Lionesses]]\n| years2         = 2000\u20132004 |clubs2 = [[Fulham L.F.C.|Fulham Ladies]]                |caps2 =    |goals2 =\n| years3         = 2004\u20132006 |clubs3 = [[Charlton Athletic L.F.C.|Charlton Athletic]] |caps3 =    |goals3 =\n| years4         = 2006\u20132010 |clubs4 = [[Arsenal W.F.C.|Arsenal Ladies]]              |caps4 = 58 |goals4 = 30\n| years5         = 2010      |clubs5 = [[Chicago Red Stars]]                          |caps5 = 21 |goals5 = 0\n| years6         = 2010\u20132013 |clubs6 = [[Arsenal W.F.C.|Arsenal Ladies]]              |caps6 = 37 |goals6 = 5\n| years7         = 2014\u20132018 |clubs7 = [[Chelsea L.F.C.|Chelsea Ladies]]              |caps7 = 61 |goals7 = 7\n| nationalyears1 = 2000\u20132016\n| nationalteam1 = [[England women's national football team|England]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 94\n| nationalgoals1 = 8\n| club-update       = 10:05, 7 July 2018 (UTC) (UTC)<ref name=\"swstats\">{{cite web|title=Katie Chapman|url=http://us.women.soccerway.com/players/katie-chapman/19365/|publisher=Soccer Way|accessdate=11 February 2018}}</ref>\n| ntupdate       = 10:05, 7 July 2018 (UTC)\n| medaltemplates = \n{{Medal|Sport|Women's [[Association football|football]]}}\n{{Medal|Country|{{fbw|ENG}}}}\n{{Medal|Competition|[[FIFA Women's World Cup]]}}\n{{Medal|Bronze|[[2015 FIFA Women's World Cup|2015 Canada]]|}}\n}}\n'''Katie Sarah Chapman''' (born 15 June 1982) is an English former [[Association football|footballer]] who last played for English [[FA WSL]] club [[Chelsea L.F.C.|Chelsea Ladies]] and was a member of the [[England women's national football team|England women's national team]]. She primarily played as a [[Defensive midfielder|central midfielder]], although she was also deployed in [[Defender (association football)#Centre back|central defence]] while playing for England. Chapman has been described as \"a physical player who handles a brunt of the dirty work in the middle of the pitch.\"<ref name=chicago/><ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/2977227.stm|title=Katie Chapman|publisher=BBC Sport|date=25 April 2003 |accessdate=1 April 2011}}</ref> Her playing ability, profile and influence have drawn comparisons to former [[England national football team|England]] captain [[David Beckham]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://football.guardian.co.uk/pictures/image/0,8556,-10104600971,00.html|title=Katie Chapman|publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]]|accessdate=1 April 2011|location=London}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-1212228/Meet-Englands-star-midfielder-mother-wont-lining-Croatia-tonight.html|title=Move over Beckham, meet England's other star midfielder... the mother-of-two set to make football history in Euro final|date=9 September 2009 |publisher=[[Daily Mail]]|accessdate=1 April 2011|location=London}}</ref>\n\nChapman began her football career playing at primary school in her hometown of [[Bermondsey]]. At ten years old, she joined leading women's club [[Millwall Lionesses L.F.C.|Millwall Lionesses]]. In the 1996\u201397 season, Chapman made her senior team debut at the age of&nbsp;14. She became a regular starter in the team and also participated in the 1997 [[FA Women's Premier League Cup]] and [[FA Women's Cup]] final wins. In the 1998\u201399 campaign, Chapman won [[The Football Association|FA]] Young Player of the Year award. Already a full England international, she left Millwall in 2000 to sign a professional contract with [[Fulham L.F.C.|Fulham]]. She played on the teams that won back-to-back promotions, as well as the 2001\u201302 Premier League Cup and [[2002 FA Women's Cup Final|2002 FA Women's Cup]]. In June&nbsp;2001 Chapman was again named FA Young Player of the Year. After two years with [[Charlton Athletic L.F.C.|Charlton Athletic]] from 2004, Chapman joined [[Arsenal W.F.C.|Arsenal Ladies]] and reached prominence with the team in her first season, winning a domestic [[Treble (association football)|treble]] as well as the [[UEFA Women's Cup]]. She had missed significant sections of the 2002\u201303 and 2007\u201308 seasons through pregnancy, and spent a single season with American [[Women's Professional Soccer]] team [[Chicago Red Stars]] in 2010, before returning to Arsenal Ladies. After another pregnancy truncated her 2013 season, Chapman moved across London to sign for [[Chelsea L.F.C.|Chelsea Ladies]] in January 2014.\n\nChapman is a former [[England women's national football team|England]] U\u201318 captain. She made her senior international debut aged 17 years in May&nbsp;2000 in a [[2001 UEFA Women's Championship qualification]] match against [[Switzerland women's national football team|Switzerland]]. The following month, she made her first start against [[Norway women's national football team|Norway]]. In March&nbsp;2002 she netted her first senior international goal in a 4\u20131 [[2003 FIFA Women's World Cup qualification]] win in the [[Netherlands women's national football team|Netherlands]]. In her first spell with the national team, Chapman represented England at four major international tournaments; [[2001 UEFA Women's Championship|UEFA Euro 2001]], [[2005 UEFA Women's Championship|UEFA Euro 2005]], [[2007 FIFA Women's World Cup|2007 FIFA World Cup]] and [[2009 UEFA Women's Championship|UEFA Euro 2009]]. A two-time winner of the FA International Player of the Year in 2002 and 2010, Chapman took a break from the national team in March 2011 with a total of 82 caps and eight goals. She was recalled to the England squad in February 2014 by new manager [[Mark Sampson]] and helped them finish third at the [[2015 FIFA Women's World Cup|2015 FIFA World Cup]].\n\n==Club career==\n\n===Millwall===\nChapman joined [[Millwall Lionesses L.F.C.|Millwall Lionesses]] as a ten-year-old, and made her first team debut at 14 in 1996\u201397.<ref name=cwfc/> That season she helped the Lionesses win an [[FA Women's Cup]] and [[FA Women's Premier League Cup|Premier League Cup]] double.<ref name=euro>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/women/4605953.stm|title=England squad guide|publisher=BBC|date=3 June 2005|accessdate=29 March 2011}}</ref> [[Louise Waller|Lou Waller]], who scored Millwall's winning goal in the [[1997 FA Women's Cup Final|FA Women's Cup final victory]] over [[Barnet F.C. Ladies|Wembley]], had been Chapman's coach in the club's youth teams.<ref>{{cite news |title=Football: Lionesses bring pride to Millwall|work=[[The Independent]]|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football-lionesses-bring-pride-to-millwall-1259819.html|accessdate=24 May 2011|author=Mike Rowbottom|date=5 May 1997|location=London}}</ref> In 1998\u201399 Chapman was named Young Player of the Year in the first ever FA Women's Football Awards.<ref name=award>{{cite web |title=F.A. WOMEN'S FOOTBALL AWARDS SPONSORED BY AXA 1998/1999|work=PR Newswire|url=http://www.prnewswire.co.uk/cgi/news/release?id=52516|accessdate=28 December 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Fulham===\nIn June&nbsp;2000 Chapman signed a contract with newly professional [[Fulham L.F.C.|Fulham]] to become one of the first full-time professional female players in England.<ref name=cwfc/> It was reported that Chapman was one of the most highly paid players in the team, on an annual salary of about \u00a320,000.<ref>{{cite web |title=Article: Striking Katie leads the FA glory girls to a golden future|work=The Evening Standard|author=Patrick Sawyer|url=https://www.questia.com/read/1G1-85499354|accessdate=30 March 2011|date=7 May 2002}}</ref> In her first season with The Cottagers Chapman won the [[South West Combination Women's Football League]], the third level of women's football, and was again named FA Young Player of the Year.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.fulhamweb.co.uk/news/Katie-Chapman-Young-player-of-the-year.aspx|title=Katie confident of return|publisher=Fulham FC|date=5 June 2001|accessdate=30 March 2011}}</ref> She also played in Fulham's 1\u20130 FA Women's Cup final defeat to [[Arsenal W.F.C.|Arsenal]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/3004925/Womens-Football-Hard-graft-pays-off-for-Arsenal-as-Banks-grabs-decider-to-dent-Fulhams-ambitions.html|title=Women's Football: Hard graft pays off for Arsenal as Banks grabs decider to dent Fulham's ambitions|publisher=The Telegraph|date=7 May 2001|accessdate=30 March 2011|author=Sam Wallace|location=London}}</ref>\n\nIn 2001\u201302 Chapman helped Fulham win the [[FA Women's Premier League Southern Division]] and promotion to the top flight. She also scored two goals in the 7\u20131 Premier League Cup final win over [[Birmingham City L.F.C.|Birmingham City]], after which Fulham's manager Gaute Haugenes claimed Chapman was good enough to play in any national side in the world.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thefa.com/TheFACup/FACompetitions/TheFAWomensPLCup/NewsandFeatures/2002/10970.aspx|title=Birmingham City 1\u20137 Fulham|publisher=TheFA.com|date=7 April 2002|accessdate=30 March 2011|author=Matthew Cook}}</ref> Chapman then scored the winning goal in the [[2002 FA Women's Cup Final|2\u20131 FA Women's Cup final victory]] over Doncaster Belles, a volley from 20&nbsp;yards.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/news-and-comment/fulham-too-professional-for-battling-belles-650449.html|title=\nFulham too professional for battling Belles|publisher=The Independent|author=Tony Leighton|accessdate=3 October 2010|date=7 May 2005|location=London}}</ref> In Conclusion to the 2001\u201302 season, Chapman went on to be awarded the Ladies Player of the Season,<ref>{{cite news|title=Chapman wins award|url=http://www.fulhamfc.com/news/2002/may/07/chapman-wins-award|publisher=Fulham Official Website|date=7 May 2002|accessdate=10 April 2014}}</ref> as well as, winning the Nationwide International Player of the Year award.<ref>{{cite news|title=Chapman wins award|url=http://www.fulhamfc.com/news/2002/may/27/chapman-wins-award|publisher=Fulham Official Website|date=27 May 2002|accessdate=10 April 2014}}</ref>\n\nChapman sat out most of the following season due to pregnancy, as Fulham won a treble of [[FA Women's Premier League National Division]], FA Women's Cup and Premier League Cup. She made the announcement during half-time of a match against [[Tranmere Rovers L.F.C.|Tranmere Rovers]], and was promptly substituted by Haugenes \u2013 who quipped that he was not permitted to have 12&nbsp;players on the pitch at once.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://jacksonville.com/tu-online/stories/091302/spo_10438363.html|title=\nSports Briefs|publisher=Jacksonville.com|accessdate=31 March 2011|date=13 September 2002}}</ref> When Chapman returned to action, in the [[FA Women's Community Shield]] in August&nbsp;2003, Fulham were no longer a professional outfit.<ref name=Charlton>{{cite news|url=http://tickets.cafc.co.uk/newsview.ink?nid=20353&newstype=l|title=Charlton add Chapman to ranks|publisher=Charlton Athletic FC|author=Matt Wright|accessdate=30 March 2011|date=14 July 2004|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20110831043408/http://tickets.cafc.co.uk/newsview.ink?nid=20353&newstype=l|archivedate=31 August 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> She represented Fulham in that season's [[UEFA Women's Champions League|Uefa Women's Cup]] campaign.<ref name=uefa>{{cite news|url=http://www.uefa.com/womenschampionsleague/news/newsid=95230.html |title=Fulham fire on all cylinders|publisher=[[UEFA]].com |date=25 August 2003 |accessdate=5 February 2013}}</ref> In March&nbsp;2004 Chapman played in Fulham's Premier League Cup final defeat to Charlton Athletic.<ref name=Charlton/>\n\n===Charlton Athletic===\nJuly&nbsp;2004 saw Chapman depart Fulham to sign for Charlton,<ref name=Charlton/> making her debut in a 1\u20130 Community Shield win over Arsenal at [[Broadhall Way]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.womenssoccerscene.co.uk/womens-football-news-2004-2005/040812-0.htm|title=Charlton capture Community Shield|publisher=Women's Soccer Scene|date=12 August 2004|accessdate=31 May 2011}}</ref> She played in The Addicks' 3\u20130 defeat to Arsenal in the Premier League Cup final in March&nbsp;2005.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablese/eng-wom05.html|title=\nEngland (Women) 2004/05|publisher=RSSSF.com|accessdate=30 March 2011|date=17 June 2006|author=David Shannon}}</ref> She then missed the conclusion of the 2004\u201305 season, including Charlton's FA Women's Cup win, with a broken hand sustained on international duty.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thefa.com/England/womens-seniors/News/2005/Katie_confident_ofreturn|title=Katie confident of return|publisher=TheFA.com|date=5 May 2005|accessdate=29 March 2011}}</ref> In March&nbsp;2006 Chapman played in her third successive Premier League Cup final, as Charlton beat Arsenal 2\u20131.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/women/4776978.stm|title=Arsenal 1\u20132 Charlton Athletic|publisher=BBC Sport|author=Tony Leighton|date=5 March 2006|accessdate=31 March 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Arsenal===\nChapman signed for league champions Arsenal in July&nbsp;2006.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thefa.com/Leagues/WomensPremierLeague/NewsAndFeatures/2006/Chapman_movesto_Gunners|title=Chapman now a Gunner|publisher=TheFA.com|date=19 July 2006|accessdate=31 March 2011}}</ref> She marked her Gunners debut with the opening goal in a 3\u20130 Community Shield win over [[Everton L.F.C.|Everton]] at [[Gresty Road]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.arsenal.com/match/report/0708comm-shield-arsenal-ladies-3-everton-0?tab=report|title=Comm Shield: Arsenal Ladies 3 Everton 0|publisher=Arsenal.com|date=2 August 2006|accessdate=31 March 2011|author=Chris Harris}}</ref> In Chapman's first season at the club, Arsenal claimed an unprecedented [[Tuples in association football|quadruple]], winning the FA Premier League Cup, FA Women's Cup, FA Women's Premier League and the UEFA Women's Cup.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thefa.com/England/womens-seniors/News/2007/AwardsPiece|title=A season of achievement|publisher=TheFA.com|date=23 May 2007|accessdate=31 March 2011}}</ref> Arsenal's assistant coach [[Emma Hayes]] described Chapman as \"a rock that makes everything around her better. She was the engine and heartbeat of the successful quadruple-winning team.\"<ref name=chicago>{{cite news|url=http://www.womensprosoccer.com/Home/chicago/news/press_releases/091202-chapman-signing.aspx|title=Red Stars Sign Arsenal's Katie Chapman|publisher=WomensProSoccer.com|date=2 December 2009|accessdate=31 March 2011|author=Charlie Corr|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100912120402/http://www.womensprosoccer.com/Home/chicago/news/press_releases/091202-chapman-signing.aspx|archivedate=12 September 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Midway through the 2007\u201308 season, Chapman's second pregnancy ruled her out of the rest of the campaign.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/women/7229059.stm|title=Westwood earns England Women spot|publisher=BBC|date=5 February 2008|accessdate=31 March 2011}}</ref>\n\nDuring 2008\u201309 Chapman returned to help Arsenal retain the league title; she also scored the opening goal in the 2009 FA Women's Cup final at [[Pride Park Stadium|Pride Park]] against [[Sunderland A.F.C. Women|Sunderland Ladies]], in a game which ended 2\u20131 to Arsenal.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2009/may/04/womens-fa-cup-final-arsenal-sunderland|title=Arsenal give Vic Akers the right send-off with the wrong performance|publisher=The Guardian|author=Tony Leighton|date=4 May 2009|accessdate=4 June 2010|location=London}}</ref> She had also featured in Arsenal's 5\u20130 Premier League Cup final win over Doncaster Rovers Belles.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thefa.com/TheFACup/FACompetitions/TheFAWomensPLCup/NewsandFeatures/2009/Arsenal_lift_the_cup|title=Arsenal lift The Cup|author=Glenn Lavery|publisher=TheFA.com|date=26 February 2009|accessdate=31 March 2011}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Katie Chapman 2014 (cropped).jpg|thumb|left|Captaining Chelsea in July 2014]]\n\n===Chicago Red Stars===\nIn December&nbsp;2009 [[Women's Professional Soccer|WPS]] club [[Chicago Red Stars]] signed Chapman,<ref name=chicago/> who cited the need for a new challenge.<ref name=cnj>{{cite news|publisher=Camden New Journal|title=Women's Football: Katie Chapman returns to Arsenal Ladies|url=http://www.camdennewjournal.com/sports/2010/nov/womens-football-katie-chapman-returns-arsenal-ladies|date=10 November 2010|author=Sarah Marsh|accessdate=30 May 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722022840/http://www.camdennewjournal.com/sports/2010/nov/womens-football-katie-chapman-returns-arsenal-ladies|archivedate=22 July 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The Red Stars announced that Chapman would join the club in time for the [[2010 Women's Professional Soccer season|2010 WPS season]], joining up with former Arsenal coach Emma Hayes and England team-mate [[Karen Carney]].<ref>{{cite news|publisher=BBC Sport|title=England women's Katie Chapman joins Chicago Red Stars|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/women/8392094.stm|date=2 December 2009}}</ref> After making 21&nbsp;appearances during the campaign, Chapman negotiated a mutual release from her contract and returned to Arsenal.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=WomensProSoccer.com|title=Red Stars Mutually Release Chapman|url=http://www.womensprosoccer.com/Home/chicago/news/press_releases/101001-redstars-chapman.aspx|date=1 October 2010|accessdate=31 March 2011}}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> It was reported that Chapman's husband had difficulty finding employment in America, so she returned home for the sake of her family.<ref name=cnj/>\n\n===Back to Arsenal===\nChapman rejoined Arsenal in October&nbsp;2010, with the club on domestic hiatus before the launch of the [[FA WSL]]. She was praised by manager Laura Harvey after scoring late, decisive goals against [[Rayo Vallecano Femenino]] and [[Link\u00f6pings FC]] which helped to take Arsenal through to a [[UEFA Women's Champions League]] semi-final against eventual winners [[Olympique Lyonnais (Ladies)|Lyon]].<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Arsenal.com|title=Harvey \u2013 Chapman has had a major impact|url=http://www.arsenal.com/news/ladies-news/harvey-chapman-has-had-a-major-impact|date=25 March 2011|accessdate=24 May 2011|author=Chris Harris|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111020154026/http://www.arsenal.com/news/ladies-news/harvey-chapman-has-had-a-major-impact|archivedate=20 October 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In May&nbsp;2011, following injuries to [[Faye White]] and [[Jayne Ludlow]], Chapman [[Captain (association football)|captained]] the Arsenal team which beat [[Bristol Academy W.F.C.|Bristol Academy]] 2\u20130 at the [[Ricoh Arena]] to reclaim the FA Women's Cup.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=TheFA.com|title=Chapman's pride|url=http://www.thefa.com/TheFACup/FACompetitions/TheFAWomensCup/2010-11/TheFinal/Arsenal-BristolAcademy/Post-Match/Katie-Chapman|date=22 May 2011|accessdate=24 May 2011|author=Glenn Lavery}}</ref>\n\nArsenal and Chapman won the first two editions of the FA WSL in [[2011 FA WSL|2011]] and [[2012 FA WSL|2012]]. In March 2013 Arsenal announced that Chapman was seven months pregnant and would miss the first half of the [[2013 FA WSL|2013]] campaign.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]]|title=Congratulations Katie Chapman|url=http://www.arsenal.com/news/news-archive/congratulations-katie-chapman|date=19 March 2013|accessdate=1 June 2013}}</ref> She returned to the team in a friendly win over [[Coventry City L.F.C.|Coventry City]] in July 2013, following the birth of her third son.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]]|title=Coventry Ladies 0\u20134 Arsenal Ladies|url=http://www.arsenal.com/match/report/1314/post/ladies/coventry-ladies-0-4-arsenal-ladies|date=24 July 2013|accessdate=8 September 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 August 2013, Chapman made a substitute appearance in Arsenal's 3\u20130 FA WSL win over [[Liverpool L.F.C.|Liverpool]]. The FA decreed she had not been properly registered and Arsenal were deducted three points. The blunder meant that Arsenal \u2013 champions for the last nine consecutive seasons \u2013 could not finish higher than third and would not qualify for the 2014\u201315 UEFA Women's Champions League, unless they won the 2013\u201314 competition.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[British Broadcasting Corporation]]|title=Arsenal Ladies: FA deducts points after Chapman sub appearance|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/24115826|date=16 September 2013|accessdate=21 September 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Chelsea===\nIn January 2014, Chelsea announced the double [[Transfer (association football)|transfer]] of Chapman and [[Gilly Flaherty]] from Arsenal. The move reunited Chapman with Emma Hayes, her coach from Arsenal and Chicago. She hoped that training more regularly with Chelsea would kick start her international career.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[British Broadcasting Corporation]]|title=Katie Chapman has England hopes after sealing Chelsea switch|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/25667416|date=9 January 2014|accessdate=9 January 2014|first=Alistair|last=Magowan}}</ref> In August 2015 Chapman captained Chelsea in their FA Women's Cup [[2015 FA Women's Cup Final|final]] against [[Notts County L.F.C.|Notts County]], the first time the event had been staged at [[Wembley Stadium]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Chapman|first1=Katie|title=Women's FA Cup: Katie Chapman's road to Wembley|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/get-inspired/33689594|accessdate=1 August 2015|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|date=29 July 2015}}</ref> She described the experience as \"overwhelming\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Women's FA Cup final is 'great history' \u2013 Chelsea's Katie Chapman|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/33738883|accessdate=1 August 2015|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|date=31 July 2015}}</ref> Chelsea's 1\u20130 win before a Cup final record 30,710 crowd secured the club's first major trophy. It was the ninth FA Women's Cup winner's medal of Chapman's career.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Garry|first1=Tom|title=Women's FA Cup final: Chelsea Ladies 1\u20130 Notts County Ladies|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/33541364|accessdate=1 August 2015|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|date=1 August 2015}}</ref> In October 2015 she played in Chelsea's 4\u20130 win over Sunderland which secured the club's first [[FA WSL]] title and a League and Cup \"[[Double (association football)|double]]\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Garry|first1=Tom|title=WSL 1: Chelsea Ladies 4\u20130 Sunderland Ladies|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/34372478|accessdate=8 October 2015|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|date=4 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[2018 FA Women's Cup Final]], Chapman secured a record 10th winner's medal as Chelsea beat Arsenal 3\u20131 at Wembley.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Garry |first1=Tom |title=Katie Chapman: Record 10th Women's FA Cup for Chelsea captain, but 'more to come' |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/44012506 |accessdate=7 July 2018 |publisher=[[BBC Sport]] |date=6 May 2018}}</ref> Five days later she announced that she was retiring from football at the end of the 2017\u201318 season.<ref>{{cite news |title=Katie Chapman: Chelsea Ladies captain & England midfielder to retire this summer |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/44074631 |accessdate=7 July 2018 |publisher=[[BBC Sport]] |date=10 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nAs a 16-year-old, Chapman was called into the [[England women's national football team|England]] U\u201318 team, and captained her country at that level.<ref name=cwfc/> Chapman made her senior debut for England at 17, during the [[2001 UEFA Women's Championship qualification]] tournament, replacing [[Samantha Britton]] after 73&nbsp;minutes of a 1\u20130 win over [[Switzerland women's national football team|Switzerland]] in [[Bristol]] on 6&nbsp;May&nbsp;2000.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thefa.com/England/womens-seniors/News/2000/2613|title=Smith makes her mark|publisher=TheFA.com|date=7 May 2000|accessdate=29 March 2011}}</ref> Chapman's first senior start came in an 8\u20130 reverse to [[Norway women's national football team|Norway]] in June&nbsp;2000. Despite the heavy defeat she was praised for her performance by national coach [[Hope Powell]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thefa.com/England/womens-seniors/News/2000/2628|title=Powell's hopes hit|publisher=TheFA.com|date=2 June 2000|accessdate=29 March 2011}}</ref> England qualified for the final tournament with Chapman named Player of the Match in the away leg of the play-off win over [[Ukraine women's national football team|Ukraine]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thefa.com/England/womens-seniors/News/2000/1036|title=Striking result takes England close|publisher=TheFA.com|date=2 October 2000|accessdate=29 March 2011}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[2001 UEFA Women's Championship]] finals, Chapman played in all three of England's games and was praised for her performances by [[UEFA]]<ref name=cwfc/> and the victorious German coach [[Tina Theune-Meyer]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thefa.com/England/womens-seniors/News/2001/2947|title=Dawn of a new era|publisher=TheFA.com|date=3 July 2001|accessdate=29 March 2011}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Katie Chapman (cropped).jpg|thumb|left|Training with England in 2015|upright]]\n\nIn March&nbsp;2002 Chapman headed her first goal for England in a 4\u20131 [[2003 FIFA Women's World Cup qualification]] win in the [[Netherlands women's national football team|Netherlands]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2002/mar/25/newsstory.sport12?INTCMP=SRCH|title=England leave false impression of China task|publisher=The Guardian|date=25 March 2002|accessdate=30 March 2011|author=Paula Cocozza|location=London}}</ref> She was named FA International Player of the Year for 2002.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/2006341.stm|title=Spacey bags three awards|publisher=BBC|date=24 May 2002|accessdate=30 March 2011|author=Tony Leighton}}</ref> Without Chapman \u2013 pregnant with her first child \u2013 England eventually failed to reach the [[2003 FIFA Women's World Cup]] after a play-off defeat to [[France women's national football team|France]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thefa.com/England/womens-seniors/News/2002/27096|title=Chapman's China dreams|publisher=TheFA.com|date=15 October 2002|accessdate=29 March 2011}}</ref>\n\nDespite a hand injury, Chapman also played every minute of all three games<ref>{{cite news|url=https://tickets.cafc.co.uk/newsview.ink?nid=22282&newstype=l|title=Euro exit for Charlton trio|publisher=Charlton Athletic|accessdate=30 March 2011|date=12 June 2005|author=Matt Wright|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110831045135/https://tickets.cafc.co.uk/newsview.ink?nid=22282&newstype=l|archivedate=31 August 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> for England at the [[2005 UEFA Women's Championship]], now featuring in midfield as she did at club level.<ref name=euro/> Her initial appearances for the national team had come in central defence.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sportacademy/hi/sa/football/video_masterclasses/newsid_2125000/2125225.stm|title=No way past Katie Chapman|publisher=BBC|accessdate=30 March 2011|date=12 July 2002}}</ref> At the [[2007 FIFA Women's World Cup]] Chapman started three matches, missing the group game against [[Argentina women's national football team|Argentina]] after picking up her second booking of the tournament during an impressive performance against [[Germany women's national football team|Germany]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2007/sep/14/newsstory.sport?INTCMP=SRCH|title=Heroic England hold Germany at bay|publisher=The Guardian|date=14 September 2007|accessdate=30 March 2011|author=Anna Kessel|location=London}}</ref>\n\nOn Chapman's return to the team she scored two goals in a [[Cyprus Cup]] win over [[South Africa women's national football team|South Africa]] in March&nbsp;2009. It was her first appearance for England since October&nbsp;2007, due to the birth of her second child.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thefa.com/England/womens-seniors/News/2009/Chapmans_childs_play|title=Chapman's Childs Play|publisher=TheFA.com|date=7 March 2009|accessdate=29 March 2011}}</ref> In May&nbsp;2009, Chapman was one of the first 17 female players to be given central contracts by [[The Football Association]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/women/8050189.stm|title=England Women awarded contracts|publisher=BBC Sport|date=14 May 2009|accessdate=29 July 2009}}</ref> She was an ever-present in midfield during England's run to the [[2009 UEFA Women's Championship]] final.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thefa.com/England/All-Teams/Players/C/Katie-Chapman|title=Katie Chapman|publisher=TheFA.com|accessdate=30 March 2011}}</ref> In 2010 Chapman was named FA International Player of the Year for the second time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefa.com/GetIntoFootball/Players/PlayersPages/WomensAndGirls/NewsandFeatures/2010/FAWFA10 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120919123655/http://www.thefa.com/GetIntoFootball/Players/PlayersPages/WomensAndGirls/NewsandFeatures/2010/FAWFA10 |url-status=dead |archive-date=19 September 2012 |title=Key figures honoured at Women's awards |publisher=TheFA.com |accessdate=5 September 2010 }}</ref>\n\nAhead of a March&nbsp;2011 friendly against [[United States women's national soccer team|United States]], Chapman unexpectedly withdrew from the England squad and quit international football. The decision, related to Chapman's family commitments, was reported to have left England's [[2011 FIFA Women's World Cup|World Cup]] preparations in disarray.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/women/9439172.stm|title=England hit by Katie Chapman retirement|publisher=BBC Sport|date=28 March 2011|accessdate=29 March 2011|author=Tony Leighton}}</ref> Hope Powell praised Chapman as \"a wonderful servant to England over the years\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.uefa.com/womensworldcup/news/newsid=1613092.html|title=Chapman steps back from England team|publisher=[[UEFA]].com|date=29 March 2011|accessdate=29 March 2011}}</ref> Chapman later confirmed she had been unhappy about a perceived lack of support with childcare costs and arrangements while on international duty.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2012/oct/15/few-working-mums-in-sport|title=Why is there only one working mum in elite football?|publisher=[[The Guardian]]|date=15 October 2012|accessdate=8 September 2013|first=Carrie|last=Dunn}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2013/aug/22/hope-powell-england-players|title=Hope Powell's ruthless brilliance will not be missed by England's players|publisher=[[The Guardian]]|date=22 August 2013|accessdate=8 September 2013|first=Anna|last=Kessel}}</ref> At the 2011 World Cup, Powell stressed that the FA had tried hard to accommodate Chapman's requirements: \"Katie was away with us in 2009 when we paid for her family to come along but at the end of the day there is not a bottomless pit of money in the women's game.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.express.co.uk/sport/football/252169/Katie-Chapman-s-boys-mean-the-World-to-her|title=Katie Chapman's boys mean the World to her|publisher=[[Daily Express]]|date=12 June 2011|accessdate=8 September 2013|first=Colin|last=Mafham}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2013, after Powell had been sacked, Chapman gave an interview to [[BBC Radio 5 Live]] in which she lamented her treatment. Chapman recalled that she asked for time off to look after her children in a brief conversation with Powell, only to receive an e-mail cancelling her central contract three hours later. She clarified that she had never retired from international football and that she still wanted to return and win 100 caps.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[British Broadcasting Corporation]]|title=England's Katie Chapman queries FA stance on motherhood|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/24078769|date=14 September 2013|accessdate=21 September 2013}}</ref>\n\nPowell's successor [[Mark Sampson]] eventually recalled Champman to the national team squad in February 2015, for a friendly against the United States in [[Milton Keynes]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Katie Chapman recalled by England for USA friendly|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/31132685|accessdate=8 February 2015|publisher=[[British Broadcasting Corporation]]|date=4 February 2015}}</ref> In May 2015 Sampson confirmed Chapman in his final squad for the [[2015 FIFA Women's World Cup]], to be hosted in Canada.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lavery|first1=Glenn|title=England squad named for FIFA Women's World Cup|url=http://www.thefa.com/news/england/womens/2015/may/world-cup-canada-2015-squad-announcement|accessdate=28 May 2015|publisher=[[The Football Association]]|date=11 May 2015}}</ref> During the tournament Chapman celebrated her 33rd birthday and her husband and three sons flew out for a surprise visit.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Taylor|first1=Louise|title=England's Katie Chapman ready for mother of all battles against Canada|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2015/jun/25/england-katie-chapman-canada-womens-world-cup|accessdate=1 August 2015|publisher=[[The Guardian]]|date=25 June 2015}}</ref> Despite her selection she made further public criticisms of the FA's ongoing lack of childcare arrangements.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Magowan |first1=Alistair |title=Katie Chapman: England player says FA can still improve childcare |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/32699605 |accessdate=7 July 2018 |publisher=[[BBC Sport]] |date=11 May 2015}}</ref> England eventually finished in third place after Chapman, starting her fifth match of the tournament, helped them beat Germany 1\u20130 in the bronze medal play-off.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Wittenberg|first1=Daniel|title=Women's World Cup: England claim bronze|url=http://www.chelseafc.com/news/latest-news/2015/07/women_s-world-cup--england-claim-bronze.html|accessdate=1 August 2015|publisher=[[Chelsea F.C.]]|date=28 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nChapman's final appearance for England came in April 2016. In September 2017 she accused Sampson of leaving her out of the national team because she was getting divorced.<ref name=\"divorce\">{{cite news |title=Katie Chapman 'not picked for England since divorce' |url=http://sport.bt.com/football/katie-chapman-not-picked-for-england-since-divorce-S11364210993646 |accessdate=7 July 2018 |publisher=[[BT Sport]] |date=9 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n===International goals===\n:''Scores and results list England's goal tally first.''\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! # !! Date !! Venue !! Opponent !! Score !! Result !! Competition\n|-\n| 1. || 23 March 2002 || [[Zuiderpark Stadion]], [[The Hague]] || {{fbw|NED}} || '''1'''\u20130 || 4\u20131 || [[2003 FIFA Women's World Cup qualification (UEFA)#Group 4|2003 World Cup qualifier]]\n|-\n| 2. || 27 October 2005 || Tapolca Stadium, [[Tapolca]] || {{fbw|HUN}} || '''5'''\u20130 || 13\u20130 || [[2007 FIFA Women's World Cup qualification (UEFA)|2007 World Cup qualifier]]\n|-\n| 3. || 13 May 2007 || [[Priestfield Stadium]], [[Gillingham, Kent|Gillingham]] || {{fbw|NIR}} || '''3'''\u20130 || 4\u20130 || [[2009 UEFA Women's Championship qualification|Euro 2009 qualifier]]\n|-\n| 4. || rowspan=\"2\" | 17 May 2007 || rowspan=\"2\" | [[Roots Hall]], [[Southend-on-Sea]] || rowspan=\"2\" | {{fbw|ISL}} || '''2'''\u20130 || rowspan=\"2\" | 4\u20130 || rowspan=\"2\" | [[Exhibition game|Friendly]]\n|-\n| 5. || '''4'''\u20130\n|-\n| 6. || rowspan=\"2\" | 5 March 2009 || rowspan=\"2\" | [[GSZ Stadium]], [[Larnaca]] || rowspan=\"2\" | {{fbw|RSA}} || '''5'''\u20130 || rowspan=\"2\" | 6\u20130 || rowspan=\"2\" | [[2009 Cyprus Cup]]\n|-\n| 7. || '''6'''\u20130\n|-\n| 8. || 1 April 2010 || [[The Den|New Den]], [[London]] || {{fbw|ESP}} || '''1'''\u20130 || 1\u20130 || [[2011 FIFA Women's World Cup qualification \u2013 UEFA Group 5#England v Spain|2011 World Cup qualifier]]\n|}\n\n===Great Britain Olympic===\nIn June 2012 Chapman was not included in the final 18-player [[Great Britain women's Olympic football team|Great Britain]] squad for the [[Football at the 2012 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's tournament|2012 London Olympics]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/olympics/18592483|title=Team GB women's squad for London 2012 announced|publisher=BBC Sport|date=26 June 2012|accessdate=8 September 2013}}</ref> She had made the 35-player longlist but was hurt and disappointed to be overlooked for the event in her home city. Chapman felt that her decision to withdraw from the England squad had caused Hope Powell \u2013 who managed Great Britain as well as England \u2013 to leave her out.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://beamagazine.wordpress.com/2012/08/14/interview-arsenals-katie-chapman-talks-about-the-olympics-england-and-motherhood/|title=Interview: Arsenal's Katie Chapman talks about the Olympics, England, and motherhood|publisher=Bea Magazine|date=14 August 2012|accessdate=8 September 2013|last=Dunn|first=Carrie}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nChapman has three sons with former husband Mark Wilkinson, a [[construction worker]] she met while he coached at Millwall Lionesses.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Chaudhury |first1=Vivek |title=Footballers husbands |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/footballers-husbands-7270548.html |accessdate=7 July 2018 |publisher=[[London Evening Standard]] |date=3 June 2005}}</ref> During the pregnancies Chapman trained until two weeks before the birth, then resumed training six weeks afterwards.<ref name=koski>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/home/you/article-1362607/England-women-s-football-team-aiming-win-World-Cup.html|title=A whole different ball game: Meet the women aiming to win the World Cup\n|publisher=[[Daily Mail]]|date=11 March 2011|accessdate=29 March 2011|author=John Koski|location=London}}</ref> In 2002\u201303 Chapman sat out Fulham's treble winning season while pregnant with Harvey, but returned in August&nbsp;2003 and played in the [[FA Women's Community Shield]] win over [[Doncaster Rovers Belles|Doncaster Belles]].<ref name=cwfc>{{cite web|url=http://www.freewebs.com/macacresswell4eva/englandwomen.htm |title=England women Fixtures and Results, 2004/05 |publisher=Cresswell Wanderers FC |accessdate=11 October 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121024012842/http://www.freewebs.com/macacresswell4eva/englandwomen.htm |archivedate=24 October 2012 }}</ref>\n\nAs of January&nbsp;2008, Chapman announced she was pregnant with Riley, and as a result played no further part in Arsenal's 2007\u201308 season. Riley was born on 8&nbsp;July. Chapman returned to Arsenal for the 2008\u201309 season and assisted in their 5\u20131 victory over [[Nottingham Forest L.F.C.|Nottingham Forest Ladies]], in Carlton, on 18&nbsp;September.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.arsenal.com/match/report/0809/post/ladies/nottm-forest-v-arsenal-ladies?tab=report|title=Nottingham Forest 1 \u2013 5 Arsenal|publisher=Arsenal|date=18 September 2009|accessdate=29 March 2011}}</ref> She divorced Mark in 2016.<ref name=\"divorce\" />\n\nChapman is a lifelong supporter of [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]],<ref name=millwall>{{cite news|url=http://www.millwallfc.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10367~2056533,00.html|title=Three Lions on her shirt...|publisher=Millwall FC|date=21 May 2010|accessdate=29 March 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100530124120/http://www.millwallfc.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10367~2056533,00.html|archivedate=30 May 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and has trained as a [[beautician]].<ref name=koski/> Katie has a twin, Sophie, who she played alongside at Millwall Lionesses.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content.espressoeducation.com/espresso/modules/t2_special_reports/sport/world_cup_2002/www_girls_football/girlsfootball/stars.html|title=Meet the Stars|publisher=[[The Football Association]]|accessdate=27 October 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130122233750/http://content.espressoeducation.com/espresso/modules/t2_special_reports/sport/world_cup_2002/www_girls_football/girlsfootball/stars.html|archivedate=22 January 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n[[File:Chelsea Ladies 1 Notts County Ladies 0 (20183103506) (2).jpg|thumb|right|Waiting to be interviewed on the pitch at Wembley Stadium, August 2015]]\n\n'''Millwall Lionesses'''\n*[[FA Women's Cup]]: 1996\u201397{{citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n*[[FA Women's Premier League Cup]]: 1996\u201397{{citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n\n'''Fulham'''\n*[[FA Women's Premier League National Division]]: 2002\u201303{{citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n*[[FA Women's Premier League Southern Division]]: 2001\u201302{{citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n*[[South East Combination Women's Football League]]: 2000\u201301{{citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n*FA Women's Cup: 2001\u201302, 2002\u201303{{citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n*FA Women's Premier League Cup: 2001\u201302, 2002\u201303{{citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n\n'''Charlton Athletic'''\n*FA Women's Cup: 2004\u201305{{citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n*FA Women's Premier League Cup: 2005\u201306{{citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n\n'''Arsenal'''\n*[[FA WSL]]: 2011, 2012{{citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n*FA Women's Premier League National Division: 2006\u201307, 2007\u201308, 2008\u201309{{citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n*[[UEFA Women's Champions League|UEFA Women's Cup]]: 2006\u201307{{citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n*FA Women's Cup: 2006\u201307, 2007\u201308, 2008\u201309, 2010\u201311{{citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n*FA Women's Premier League Cup: 2006\u201307, 2008\u201309{{citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n*[[FA WSL Continental Cup]]: 2011{{citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n*[[FA Women's Community Shield]]: 2006{{citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n\n'''Chelsea'''\n*FA WSL: 2015{{citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n*FA Women's Cup: 2014\u201315, 2017\u201318{{citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n\n'''England'''\n*[[Cyprus Cup]]: 2009, 2015{{citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n*[[UEFA Women's Championship]] runner-up: [[2009 UEFA Women's Championship|2009]]<ref>{{cite web |title=UEFA Women's EURO 2009 - Final |url=https://www.uefa.com/womenseuro/season=2009/matches/round=15050/match=2001423/postmatch/lineups/index.html |publisher=UEFA |accessdate=7 July 2019 |date=10 September 2009}}</ref>\n*[[FIFA Women's World Cup]] third place: [[2015 FIFA Women's World Cup|2015]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://resources.fifa.com/mm/document/tournament/competition/02/66/09/64/eng_51_0704_ger-eng_fulltime.pdf |date=4 July 2015 |title=Match for third place - Match report |publisher=FIFA |format=PDF |accessdate=7 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n'''Individual'''\n<!--LEAGUE AND FEDERATION-SANCTIONED AWARDS ONLY. No fan or magazine-voted awards. Listed in chronological order from last time won.-->\n*FA Women's Young Player of the Year: 1998\u201399, 2000\u201301{{citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n*FA Women's International Player of the Year: 2001\u201302, 2009\u201310{{citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*{{FIFA player}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110423152659/http://www.arsenal.com/ladies/players/katie-chapman Profile] at Arsenal.com\n*[http://www.thefa.com/England/All-Teams/Players/C/Katie-Chapman Katie Chapman] at the FA website\n*[https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http://www.geocities.com/titch2401/katiechapman.html&date=2009-10-25+23:07:34  Unofficial website]\n\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Awards\n| bg = Gold\n| bordercolor = #000000\n| list1 = \n{{FA Women's Young Player of the Year}}\n{{FA Women's International Player of the Year}}\n}}\n{{Navboxes\n| title = England squads\n| bg = white\n| fg = #CF081F\n| bordercolor = #0B0B3F\n| list1 = \n{{England squad 2001 UEFA Women's European Championship}}\n{{England squad 2005 UEFA Women's European Championship}}\n{{England squad 2007 FIFA Women's World Cup}}\n{{England squad 2009 UEFA Women's European Championship}}\n{{England squad 2015 FIFA Women's World Cup}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chapman, Katie}}\n[[Category:1982 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Bermondsey]]\n[[Category:English women's footballers]]\n[[Category:England women's international footballers]]\n[[Category:Arsenal W.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Chelsea F.C. Women players]]\n[[Category:Millwall Lionesses L.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Fulham L.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Charlton Athletic W.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:FA Women's National League players]]\n[[Category:Chicago Red Stars (WPS) players]]\n[[Category:Expatriate women's soccer players in the United States]]\n[[Category:English expatriate sportspeople in the United States]]\n[[Category:FA Women's Super League players]]\n[[Category:English expatriate women's footballers]]\n[[Category:2007 FIFA Women's World Cup players]]\n[[Category:2015 FIFA Women's World Cup players]]\n[[Category:Women's association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Twin sportspeople]]\n", "name_user": "Robby.is.on", "label": "safe", "comment": "Date formats perMOS:DATEFORMATbyscript.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Katie_Chapman"}
{"title_page": "District of Columbia Public Schools", "text_new": "{{short description|American public school system of the Distric of Columbia}}\n{{redirect|Washington Public Schools|similarly named school districts|Washington School District (disambiguation)|and|Columbia School District (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use American English|date=December 2017}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2017}}\n{{Infobox school district\n|name                = District of Columbia Public Schools\n|logo                = DCPSlogo.png\n|motto               = \n|type                = Public\n|grades              = PK\u201312\n|established         = {{Start date|1805}}\n|closed              = \n|region              = Mid-Atlantic, Southeast\n|country             = United States\n|location            = 1200 First Street, NE, Washington, DC 20002\n|coordinates         = <!-- {{Coord|||dim:250_region:US-_type:edu|name=District office|display=inline,title}} -->\n|president           = \n|vice-president      = \n|superintendent_type = Chancellor\n|superintendent      = Dr. Lewis Ferebee (acting)\n|asst_superintendent = \n|accreditations      = <!-- or | accreditation = -->\n|schools             = 111 (2014\u20132015 academic year)\n|budget              = $701,344,630\n|us_nces_district_id = <!-- {{NCES District ID||district_name=|access_date=}} -->\n|students            = 47,548\n|faculty             = \n|teachers            = 4,137\n|staff               =  <!-- 9.633 IS THIS 9,633? -->\n|ratio               = 11.49\n|conference          = \n|mascot              = \n|colors              = \n|schedule            = \n|website             = {{URL|dcps.dc.gov}}\n}}\n{{Education in the U.S.}}\n'''District of Columbia Public Schools''' ('''DCPS''') is the local, traditional [[school district|public school system]] of [[Washington, D.C.]], the [[capital city|capital]] of the [[United States]]. DCPS should not be confused with the independently governed [[DC Public Charter Schools]] (DCPCS), which also operates in Washington, D.C.\n\n==Composition and enrollment==\n\n[[Washington, D.C.|District of Columbia]] Public Schools (DCPS) consists of 111<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://dcps.dc.gov/DCPS/About+DCPS/Press+Releases+and+Announcements/Press+Releases/DCPS+Opens+With+Students+Ready+to+Learn+and+Build+on+Previous+Year+Success |title=DCPS Opens With Students Ready to Learn and Build on Previous Year Success |date=August 26, 2013 |publisher=DCPS |accessdate=October 4, 2013 |quote=Today, 111 District of Columbia Public Schools (DCPS) opened... |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131004224405/http://dcps.dc.gov/DCPS/About+DCPS/Press+Releases+and+Announcements/Press+Releases/DCPS+Opens+With+Students+Ready+to+Learn+and+Build+on+Previous+Year+Success |archive-date=October 4, 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | first=| last=| title=State Education Data Profiles | url=http://nces.ed.gov/programs/stateprofiles/sresult.asp?mode=short&s1=11 | work= National Center for Education Statistics| publisher=Institute of Education Sciences, Department of Education| location=Washington, DC | pages=  | date=2009\u20132010| id= | accessdate=}}</ref>\nof the 238 public elementary and secondary schools and learning centers located in Washington, D.C. These schools have a grade span of prekindergarten to twelfth grade and, as of 2000, a kindergarten entrance age of 5 years old.<ref>{{Cite news | first=Rod| last=Paige| title=District of Columbia Public Schools--School Locator | url=http://nces.ed.gov/pubs2003/2003020.pdf| work=Overview and Inventory of State Education Reforms: 1990\u20132000| publisher=National Center for Education Statistics, Department of Education | location=Washington, DC | pages=137 | date=July 2003 | id= | accessdate=}}</ref>\nSchool is compulsory for DCPS students between the ages of 5 and 18.<ref>{{Cite news| first=| last=| title=Education Commission of the States: 2010 Collection| url=http://www.ecs.org/html/educationIssues/StateNotes/2010-StateNotes.pdf| work=2010 Collection of Education Commission of the State Notes and Policy Briefs| publisher=ECS Publications| location=Washington, DC| pages=382| year=2010| id=| accessdate=| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111207222548/http://www.ecs.org/html/educationIssues/StateNotes/2010-StateNotes.pdf| archivedate=2011-12-07| df=}}</ref>\nDCPS schools typically start the last Monday in August. The school day is generally approximately six hours.{{citation needed|date=September 2014}}\n\nThe ethnic breakdown of students enrolled in 2014 was 67% [[African American|Black]], 17% [[Hispanic and Latino Americans|Hispanic (of any race)]], 12% [[Caucasian American|non-Hispanic White]], and 4% of other races.  As of 2014, the District itself has a population that is 44% [[Caucasian American|White]] (includes [[White Hispanic]]s), 49% [[African American|Black]] and 10% [[Hispanic and Latino Americans|Hispanic (of any race)]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://quickfacts.census.gov/qfd/states/11000.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-02-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110806013655/http://quickfacts.census.gov/qfd/states/11000.html |archivedate=August 6, 2011 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> [[Gentrification]] and demographic changes in many DC neighborhoods has increased the White and Hispanic populations in the city, while reducing the Black population. In 2008, DCPS was 84.4% [[African American|Black]], 9.4% [[Hispanic and Latino Americans|Hispanic (of any race)]], 4.6% [[Caucasian American|non-Hispanic White]], and 1.6% of other races.<ref>{{Cite news | first=| last=| title=Key State Education Policies on PK\u201312 Education: 2008 | url=http://www.ccsso.org/Resources/Publications/Key_State_Education_Policies_on_PK-12_Education_2008.html | work= | publisher=Council of Chief State School Officers | location=Washington, DC | pages= 38 | year=2009 | id= | accessdate=}}</ref>\n\nFacilities reform legislation in DC has led to many school openings and closings. The most recent closure announcement is that River Terrace Elementary School and Shaed Education Campus are shutting their doors at the end of the 2010\u20132011 and 2011\u20132012 school years, respectively. Students attending River Terrace Elementary School will transition with Emery Education Campus to the Langley Building. In 2019, a proposal was submitted to close Metropolitan High School, an alternative school.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/education/dc-proposes-closing-washington-metropolitan-high-an-alternative-school/2019/11/27/4b949e00-1116-11ea-bf62-eadd5d11f559_story.html|title=DC Proposes Closing Metropolitan High School|last=|first=|date=2019-11-27|work=The Washington Post|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>  In addition, the Montessori program is expanding into the Montessori School (PS-5th grade). A part of this will be the Jefferson 6th Grade Academy, which will only house 6th grade students.\nAs of the 2009\u20132010 school year, there was a total enrollment of 43,866 students and 4,017 classroom teachers. The current student to teacher ratio is 10.92, an improvement from the 2006\u201307 ratio of 13.5.<ref>{{Cite news | first=| last=| title=2010\u20132011 Public School District Directory Information | url=http://nces.ed.gov/ccd/districtsearch/district_detail.asp?start=0&ID2=1100030 | work= National Center for Education Statistics| publisher=Institute of Education Sciences, Department of Education| location=Washington, DC | pages=  | date=2010\u20132011| id= | accessdate=}}</ref>\nHowever, student enrollment was at a peak of 72,850 students with a much larger staff totaling 12,000. The reason for this sudden enrollment drop in DCPS is that the Public Education Reform Amendment Act of 2007 separated DC Public Charter Schools (DCPCS) from District of Columbia Public Schools.\n\nThe District of Columbia passed charter school legislation in 1996, which went into effect in September 1999.  The legislation gave the District the power to grant charters for 15 years.  Although this is longer than the traditional 3\u20135 year term observed in 31 other states, a required review takes place every 5 years. 4.4% of public school students enrolled in a charter school for the 1999 academic school year; the 28 schools had a total enrollment of approx. 3,000 students. After legislation was enacted in 2007, chartering authority was placed under the D.C. Public Charter School Board and disaffiliated from DCPS. The governance of DCPS was also restructured, and the district was placed under the [[Mayoral control of schools|control of the Mayor]]. In 2010 about 38% of Washington, D.C. public school students attended 60 [[charter schools]].<ref>{{Cite news | first=Michael | last=Birnbaum | title=Taking baby steps towards charter schools | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/04/27/AR2010042704768.html| work= | publisher=Washington Pose | location=Washington, DC | pages= 18 in Casual Living | date=29 April 2010 | id= | accessdate=}}</ref> There are 52 public charter schools in the District, with 93 campuses and 30,000 students. The total number of public charter schools has been reduced from 60 schools on 96 campuses in 2008\u201309 to 53 schools on 98 campuses as of the 2011\u201312 school year. However, the addition of grades to the charter schools are still increasing enrollment and decreasing from DCPS\u2019 numbers.\n\n==Students==\n\n===Health===\nIn 2009, 43% of all DCPS public school students were overweight or obese. This was one of the highest rates in the United States.<ref>{{Cite news | first=Tim | last=Craig | title=D.C. Council targets childhood obesity | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/05/01/AR2010050103193.html?hpid=topnews| work= | publisher=Washington Post | location=Washington, DC | pages= A8 | date=2 May 2010 | id= | accessdate=}}</ref>\n\n===Dropout rate===\n\nIn the graduating class of spring 2008, the average freshman graduation rate for DCPS was 56%\u201a compared with a national average of 74.9%. This constituted a large drop from the freshman graduation rate of 68.4% in 2002 and 68.8% as recently as 2005. In just the 2008\u201309 school year alone, 1,075 black students dropped out of high school. This figure raises concern since there were 1,246 students that dropped out of DCPS schools that year.<ref>{{Cite news | first=| last=| title=Public School Graduates and Dropouts From the Common Core of Data: School Year 2008\u201309 | url=http://nces.ed.gov/pubs2011/2011312.pdf | work= National Center for Education Statistics| publisher=Institute of Education Sciences, Department of Education| location=Washington, DC | pages=  | date=2008\u20132009| id= | accessdate=}}</ref>\nHowever, these numbers are not meant to be misleading; the 62.8% freshman graduation rate of black students in 2008 was above the state average.\n\n==Governance==\n[[File:Theodore Roosevelt High School, 13th St. in upper NW, Washington, D.C..jpg|thumb|left|275px|[[Roosevelt Senior High School (Washington, DC)|Theodore Roosevelt High School]] in [[Petworth, Washington, D.C.|Petworth]].]]\nWithin DCPS, schools are classified as either a \"neighborhood school\" or a \"destination school.\" Neighborhood schools are elementary or secondary schools assigned to students based on his or her address. Destination schools are feeder-schools for elementary or secondary institutions from a school a student is already attending. Since the fall of 2009, students may choose a destination school, regardless of their neighborhood location. Locations of all of the schools and the neighborhood divides can be found on the DCPS website.<ref>{{Cite news | first=| last=| title=District of Columbia Public Schools--School Locator | url=http://www.dc.gov/DCPS/Learn+About+Schools/Find+Your+Assigned+Schools | work= | publisher=The Government of the District of Columbia | location=Washington, DC | pages=  | date= | id= | accessdate=}}</ref>\n\nFor the school year ending in spring 2007, the DCPS was governed by the [[District of Columbia State Board of Education|D.C. Board of Education]], with eleven members, including two students who had the right to debate but not to vote. Five members were elected and four were appointed by the Mayor. The Board established DCPS policies and employed a superintendent to serve as chief executive officer of the school district, responsible for day-to-day operations. Four Board members represented specific geographical boundaries and the Board President was elected at large. One condition of the District of Columbia Public Education Reform Amendment Act of 2007 was the creation of DCPS as a separate cabinet-level agency from the D.C. Board of Education. This moved DCPS within the executive branch of the District of Columbia government\u2014specifically, under Mayoral control. Currently, this means that DCPS is subordinate to District of Columbia Mayor Muriel Bowser. D.C. Mayor [[Adrian Fenty]] proposed putting the public schools under the direct control of the Mayor's Office upon taking office in January 2007. However, this reform to District of Columbia Public Schools was encouraged by his predecessor and constituents at large. It also placed all of the District of Columbia public charter schools under the care of a new board\u2014District of Columbia Public Charter School Board (PCSB). Although these schools were previously a part of DCPS, they are now considered to be a separate district controlled by the D.C. Public Charter School Board (PCSB).\n\nThe D.C. Council passed the Mayor's proposal into law but since the change amended the [[District of Columbia Home Rule Act|Home Rule Act]], the change needed to gain Federal approval before taking effect.  D.C. Delegate [[Eleanor Holmes Norton]] introduced H.R. 2080, a bill to amend the D.C. Home Rule Charter Act to provide for the Mayor's proposal. H.R. 2080 was passed by the [[United States House of Representatives]] under an expedited procedure on May 8, 2007 by a voice vote. After three U.S. Senators ([[Ben Cardin]] of [[Maryland]], [[Mary Landrieu]] of [[Louisiana]], and [[Carl Levin]] of [[Michigan]]) initially placed \"holds\" on the bill to prevent its consideration in the [[United States Senate]], the Senate agreed to pass H.R. 2080 without amendment on May 22, 2007 by unanimous consent. On May 31, 2007, the bill was presented to the President and President Bush signed H.R. 2080 into law on June 1, 2007. After the standard Congressional review period expired on June 12, 2007, the Mayor's office had direct control of the Superintendent and the school budget.  On June 12, Mayor Fenty appointed [[Michelle Rhee]] the new Chancellor, replacing Superintendent [[Clifford B. Janey]].\n\n===D.C. School Choice Incentive Act of 2003===\n{{Main|D.C. Opportunity Scholarship Program}}\n\nIn January 2004, Congress passed the D.C. School Choice Incentive Act of 2003. The law established a federally-funded private [[school voucher]] program known as the D.C. Opportunity Scholarship Program (OSP). The OSP distributes vouchers to low-income families to cover private school tuition. Because there are more eligible applicants than available vouchers, they are distributed by lottery. In 2010, a [[randomized controlled trial]] conducted under the auspices of the Department of Education examined the impacts of the OSP students, finding that it raised graduation rates.<ref>{{cite web|last=Wolf|first=Patrick|title=Evaluation of the DC Opportunity Scholarship Program: Final Report|url=http://ies.ed.gov/ncee/pubs/20104018/pdf/20104018.pdf|publisher=U.S. Department of Education -- Institute of Education Sciences}}</ref> Students who were offered vouchers had a graduation rate of 82%, while those who actually used their vouchers had a graduation rate of 91%. By comparison, the rate for students who did not receive vouchers was only 70%. The study received the Department of Education's highest rating for scientific rigor.<ref>{{cite web|title=WWC Quick Review of the Report \"Evaluation of the DC Opportunity Scholarship Program: Final Report\"|url=http://ies.ed.gov/ncee/wwc/pdf/quick_reviews/dc_final_030811.pdf|publisher=U.S. Department of Education -- Institute of Education Sciences|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130614085031/http://ies.ed.gov/ncee/wwc/pdf/quick_reviews/dc_final_030811.pdf|archivedate=2013-06-14|df=}}</ref> Over 90% of the study's participants were African American, and most of the remainder were Latino American. Further research found that students who received vouchers were 25% more likely to enroll in college than students with similar demographic characteristics who did not receive vouchers.<ref>{{cite web|title=Funding Cuts for Programs That Send More Kids to Graduation AND College? |url=http://www.edchoice.org/Blog/March-2014/Funding-Cuts-for-Programs-That-Send-More-Kids-to-G |publisher=Friedman Foundation for Educational Choice |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140307184923/http://www.edchoice.org/Blog/March-2014/Funding-Cuts-for-Programs-That-Send-More-Kids-to-G |archivedate=2014-03-07 |df= }}</ref>\n\n===D.C. Public Education Reform Amendment Act of 2007===\n\nThe Council of the District of Columbia enacted the DC Public Education Reform Amendment Act of 2007. This act established a DC public school agency based on authority given to the council in the District of Columbia Home Rule Act of 1973. The Department of Education that was established under the Mayor triggered several changes. The largest was already discussed\u2014DCPCS gained sole authority over chartering and charted schools, DCPS became subordinate to the Mayor's office. Secondly, many smaller authoritative changes took place. The first is that the State Education Office (SEO) became the State Superintendent of Education (OSSE). The four subsections of the District were reaffirmed through location-based State Board of Education selectees. In addition, the smaller eight school election wards were reaffirmed. Finally, the Commission was established through this legislature. The \"Commission\" is the Interagency Collaboration and Services Integration Commission, which includes the Mayor, Chairman of the Council of the District of Columbia, Chief Judge of the DC Superior Family Court, Superintendent of Education, Chancellor of DCPS, Chair of DCPCSB and fourteen others.\nAfter the 2007\u20132008 school year, about one-fifth of the teachers and one-third of the principals resigned, retired, or were terminated from DCPS. A very strong negative impact was initially experienced by DCPS due to the loss. A [[GAO-conducted study]]<ref>{{Cite news | first=| last=| title=District of Columbia Public Schools: Important Steps Taken to Continue Reform Efforts, But Enhanced Planning Could Improve Implementation and Sustainability| url=http://www.gao.gov/highlights/d09619high.pdf | work= Report to Congressional Requesters| publisher= United States Government Accountability Office (GAO) | location=Washington, DC | pages= | date=June 2009 | id= | accessdate=}}</ref>\nrecommended that the Mayor direct DCPS to establish planning processes for strikes and look to performance reviews from central offices to strengthen accountability. These recommendations were followed and accountability has increased through academic and financial report generation.  Increased accountability made way for other small reforms. One example is the implementation of a requirement that students entering 9th grade are now required to sit down with a school counselor and construct a course-plan to reach graduation.\n\n==No Child Left Behind compliance==\n\nIn accordance with Section 1116, a provision of the [[No Child Left Behind Act]] (NCLB), entitled \"Academic Assessment and Local Education Agency and School Improvement\", the Office of the State Superintendent of Education (OSSE) of the District of Columbia oversees compliance with [http://www.dc.gov/DCPS/In+the+Classroom/How+Students+Are+Assessed/Adequate+Yearly+Progress+(AYP) Adequate Yearly Progress] (AYP). A large portion of meeting AYP is based on standardized-tests performance; the District used the [[summative assessment]] called the District of Columbia Comprehensive Assessment System (\"DC CAS\") through the 2013-2014 school year, after which it switched to tools from the Partnership for Assessment of Readiness for College and Careers ([[PARCC]]) and the National Center and State Collaborative (NCSC).<ref>{{cite web|title=DC CAS|url=http://osse.dc.gov/service/dc-cas|website=Office of the State Superintendent of Education|publisher=Washington, DC|accessdate=7 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=How Students Are Assessed|url=http://dcps.dc.gov/DCPS/In+the+Classroom/How+Students+Are+Assessed|website=District of Columbia Public Schools|accessdate=7 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150208040753/http://dcps.dc.gov/DCPS/In+the+Classroom/How+Students+Are+Assessed|archive-date=February 8, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Assessment Glossary|url=http://dcps.dc.gov/DCPS/In+the+Classroom/How+Students+Are+Assessed/Assessment+Glossary|website=District of Columbia Public Schools|accessdate=7 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150218022539/http://dcps.dc.gov/DCPS/In+the+Classroom/How+Students+Are+Assessed/Assessment+Glossary|archive-date=February 18, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nMany schools are failing to meet AYP, even though DCPS educators offer support and tools to students to be academically successful.{{citation needed|reason=this statement needs a source to back it up and has a slanted tone.|date=March 2015}} DCPS has created an evaluation tool to assess schools by more than their standardized test scores. They call this a Quality School Review, which uses the Effective Schools Framework<ref>{{cite web|title=DCPS Effective Schools Framework|url=http://dcps.dc.gov/DCPS/About+DCPS/Strategic+Documents/Effective+Schools+Framework|website=District of Columbia Public Schools|accessdate=7 January 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150223025655/http://dcps.dc.gov/DCPS/About+DCPS/Strategic+Documents/Effective+Schools+Framework|archivedate=February 23, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref> to assess schools through rubrics on topics such as classroom observations, interviews with parents, students, teachers, and school leadership, staff surveys and reviewing artifacts (i.e. handbooks, student work).<ref>{{cite web|title=Race to the Top: District of Columbia Report Year 1: School Year 2010 \u20132011|url=http://www2.ed.gov/programs/racetothetop/performance/dc-year-1.pdf|publisher=U.S. Department of Education|accessdate=7 January 2015|date=10 January 2012}}</ref> In 2007, Karin Hess of the National Center for the Improvement of Educational Assessment conducted an analysis that has also gone into the alignment of DCPS standards and the \"DC CAS Alt\", the assessment for students with cognitive disabilities.{{citation needed|reason=the previous link to the Center's home page does not enough to support this statement|date=January 2015}}\n\n==Budget==\nAccording to the U.S. Census Bureau, DCPS had a budget of $1.2 billion and spent $29,409 per pupil in FY 2009\u201310.<ref name=\"Public Education Finances: 2010\">{{cite web|title=Public Education Finances: 2010|url=http://www2.census.gov/govs/school/10f33pub.pdf|publisher=U.S. Census Bureau|accessdate=March 6, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 1989\u201390, DCPS reported that it had spent $10,200 (1999 adj. dollars) per pupil and a decade later, in 1999\u20132000, its reported per pupil expenditures had increased to $11,500.  However, those figures likely underreport DCPS's actual total per pupil expenditures. In 2012, the [[Cato Institute]]'s [[Andrew J. Coulson]] showed that DCPS's reported per pupil expenditures figures were based on incomplete data.<ref>{{cite web|last=Coulson|first=Andrew|title=Census Bureau Confirms: DC Spends $29,409 / pupil|url=http://www.cato.org/blog/census-bureau-confirms-dc-spends-29409-pupil|work=Cato.org}}</ref> That year, the U.S. Census Bureau had reported that DCPS's 2008\u201309 per pupil expenditures were $18,181, but DCPS officials had neglected to include about $400 million in spending. Informed by Coulson's observations, the U.S. Census Bureau revised its data collection methods and reported that per pupil expenditures were $28,170.<ref>{{cite web|last=Coulson|first=Andrew|title=DC Vouchers Solved? Generous Severance for Displaced Workers|url=http://www.cato.org/blog/dc-vouchers-solved-generous-severance-displaced-workers|work=Cato.org}}</ref> Those revisions are reflected in the Bureau's 2009\u201310 reports. {{Citation needed|reason=The report still has the number $18,181; one can divide anything from anything but it's not what the budget states. Clearly, Andrew Coulson likes to polish his resume via Wikipedia.|date=May 2014}}\n\nIn FY 2009\u20132010, the District received 6.7% of its total revenues for elementary and secondary education from federal sources.<ref name=\"Public Education Finances: 2010\"/>\n\n==Statistics==\nIn 2008, in terms of testing 36% of students demonstrated proficiency in mathematics and 39% demonstrated proficiency in reading.<ref name =\"time081208\">{{cite book | author = Ripley, Amanda |title = Can She Save Our Schools | publisher = Time Magazine | date = December 8, 2008}}</ref>\n\nThe average educator was paid $67,000 in 2010. A contract signed in 2010 was expected to raise that figure to $81,000 in 2012.<ref>{{Cite news | first=Bill | last=Turque | title=Fenty, teachers union promote deal | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/04/07/AR2010040704474.html?sub=AR| work= | publisher=Washington Post | location=Washington, DC | pages= B2 | date=8 April 2010 | id= | accessdate=}}</ref>\n\n==Schools and locations==\n\nAll DCPS schools are located in [[Washington, D.C.]].\n\nMany of the District's public schools are undergoing evolving relationships with the central office as they seek to compete for students leaving the system for charter schools. According to school choice researcher Erin Dillon, \"In its winning application for federal Race to the Top funds, DCPS, for example, touted its three models for autonomous schools: The aptly named 'Autonomous Schools,' which are granted autonomy as a reward for high performance; 'Partnership Schools,' which are run by outside organizations that are granted autonomy in the hope of dramatically improving performance; and the 'D.C. Collaborative for Change,' or DC3, a joint effort of some of the District\u2019s highest- and lowest-performing schools that have been granted autonomy as a tool for innovating with curriculum and professional development. (Meanwhile, highly autonomous charter schools, a growing presence in the District of Columbia, educate almost 40 percent of the city\u2019s public school students.)\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Dillon|first=Erin|title=The Road to Autonomy: Can Schools, Districts, and Central Offices Find Their Way?|url=http://www.educationsector.org/publications/road-autonomy-can-schools-districts-and-central-offices-find-their-way|work=The Road to Autonomy: Can Schools, Districts, and Central Offices Find Their Way?|publisher=Education Sector|accessdate=27 June 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110628123000/http://www.educationsector.org/publications/road-autonomy-can-schools-districts-and-central-offices-find-their-way|archive-date=June 28, 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===High schools===\n====Traditional high schools====\n[[File:Wilson-high-dc.jpg|thumb|[[Woodrow Wilson High School (Washington, D.C.)|Woodrow Wilson High School]], Tenleytown]]\n[[File:Eastern Senior High School - Washington, DC.jpg|thumb|[[Eastern High School (Washington, D.C.)|Eastern High School]], Kingman Park]]\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! width=\"175\" | S