 2004&nbsp;\u2013 June 12, 2007 || || data-sort-value=\"n\"|<ref>{{cite news|last1=Williams|first1=Clarence|last2=Strauss|first2=Valerie|title=Janey Takes Reins at Schools|work=The Washington Post|date=September 16, 2004|page=B01}}</ref><ref name=janeyfired>{{cite news|last=Nakamura|first=David|title=Fenty To Oust Janey Today|work=The Washington Post|date=June 12, 2007|page=A1}}</ref>\n|-\n| data-sort-value=\"Rhee, Michelle\"|[[Michelle Rhee]] || data-sort-value=\"2007-07-10\"|July 10, 2007&nbsp;\u2013 October 30, 2010 || data-sort-value=\"2007-06-12\"|June 12, 2007&nbsp;\u2013 July 9, 2007 (acting) || data-sort-value=\"o\"|<ref name=janeyfired /><ref>{{cite news|last=Stewart|first=Nikita|title=D.C. Council Approves Rhee as Schools Chief|work=The Washington Post|date=July 11, 2007|page=B1}}</ref><ref name=rheeresign />\n|-\n| data-sort-value=\"Henderson, Kaya\"|[[Kaya Henderson]] || data-sort-value=\"2011-06-22\"|June 22, 2011&nbsp;\u2013 September 30, 2016 || data-sort-value=\"2010-11-01\"|November 1, 2010&nbsp;\u2013 June 21, 2011 (interim) || data-sort-value=p\"|<ref name=rheeresign>{{cite news|last1=Craig|first1=Tim|last2=Turque|first2=Bill|title=Rhee to resign as schools chancellor|work=The Washington Post|date=October 13, 2010|page=A1}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Turque|first1=Bill|last2=Clement|first2=Scott|title=Ratings up for District schools|work=The Washington Post|date=June 22, 2011|page=A1}}</ref><ref name=hendersonresign>{{cite news|last1=Stein|first1=Perry|last2=Brown|first2=Emma|title=D.C. Schools Chancellor Kaya Henderson to step down, leaving legacy of progress|work=The Washington Post|date=June 29, 2016|access-date=November 6, 2016|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/education/dc-schools-chancellor-kaya-henderson-to-step-down-leaving-legacy-of-progress/2016/06/29/1189e7e6-3df8-11e6-80bc-d06711fd2125_story.html}}</ref>\n|-\n| data-sort-value=\"Davis, John\"|John Davis || || data-sort-value=\"2016-10-01\"|October 1, 2016 to February 1, 2017 (interim) || data-sort-value=\"q\"|<ref name=hendersonresign />\n|-\n| data-sort-value=\"Wilson, Antwan\"|[[Antwan Wilson]] || data-sort-value=\"2017-02-01\"|February 1, 2017&nbsp;\u2013 February 20, 2018 || || data-sort-value=\"r\"|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/education/antwan-wilson-confirmed-as-chancellor-of-dc-public-schools/2016/12/20/be7a4aa4-c6ce-11e6-bf4b-2c064d32a4bf_story.html|title=Antwan Wilson confirmed as chancellor of D.C. Public Schools|first=Alejandra|last=Matos|date=December 20, 2016|publisher=|access-date=December 10, 2017|via=www.WashingtonPost.com}}</ref><ref name=austmcg>{{cite news|last1=Austermuhle|first1=Martin|last2=McGee|first2=Kate|title=D.C. Schools Chancellor Antwan Wilson Resigns After School-Transfer Scandal|work=WAMU|date=February 20, 2018|accessdate=February 21, 2018|url=https://wamu.org/story/18/02/20/d-c-schools-chancellor-antwan-wilson-school-transfer-scandal/}}</ref>\n|-\n| data-sort-value=\"Alexander, Amanda\"|Amanda Alexander&nbsp; || || data-sort-value=\"2018-02-20\"|February 20, 2018&nbsp;\u2013 December 3, 2018 (interim) || data-sort-value=\"s\"|<ref name=austmcg />\n|-\n| data-sort-value=\"Ferebee, Lewis\"|Lewis Ferebee ||March 5, 2019 \u2013 present\n| data-sort-value=\"2018-12-03\" |December 3, 2018&nbsp;\u2013 March 4, 2019 (acting) || data-sort-value=\"t\" |<ref>{{cite press release |url=https://dcps.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-announces-dr-lewis-d-ferebee-dcps-chancellor |title=Mayor Bowser Announces Dr. Lewis D. Ferebee as DCPS Chancellor |date=December 3, 2018 |publisher=DCPS |access-date=February 25, 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://dcps.dc.gov/release/statements-confirmation-dc-public-schools-chancellor-lewis-d-ferebee|title=Statements on the Confirmation of DC Public Schools Chancellor Lewis D. Ferebee|last=|first=|date=March 5, 2019|work=District of Columbia Public School Official Home Page|access-date=March 12, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n==Graduation scandal==\nIn 2018, it was revealed by WAMU and NPR that progress achieved by the school district in relation to graduation rates the year prior had been inflated by high schools who granted diplomas to students who should have failed according to city law.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/education/dc-school-scandals-tell-me-that-its-not-great-and-that-youre-dealing-with-it/2018/03/10/b73d9cf0-1d9e-11e8-b2d9-08e748f892c0_story.html|publisher=The Washington Post|title=It Was Hailed as the National Model for School Reform. Then the Scandals Hit|author1=Emma Brown|author2=Valerie Strauss|author3=Perry Stein|date=March 10, 2018|access-date=May 6, 2018}}</ref> According to ''[[The Washington Post]]'', only 46 percent of the school district's public school students were on track to graduate in 2018 after the school system began to adhere to stricter attendance policies.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/education/dc-schools-could-face-sharp-dip-in-graduation-rate-after-scandal/2018/04/27/7f14e706-4a45-11e8-8b5a-3b1697adcc2a_story.html?noredirect=on|publisher=The Washington Post|title=D.C. Schools Could Face Sharp Dip in Graduation Rate After Scandal|author=Perry Stein|date=April 27, 2018|access-date=May 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|United States|Schools}}\n* [[List of parochial and private schools in Washington, D.C.]]\n* [[Susan E. W. Fuller]], artist, first instructor of art in the District's public schools<ref name=\"Cosentino1983\">{{cite book|author=Andrew J. Cosentino|title=The Capital Image: Painters in Washington, 1800\u20131915|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vHPqAAAAMAAJ|date=17 November 1983|publisher=Smithsonian|isbn=978-0-87474-338-8}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|District of Columbia Public Schools}}\n*[http://dcps.dc.gov/portal/site/DCPS/ District of Columbia Public Schools]\n*{{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/*/http://www.k12.dc.us|title=District of Columbia Public Schools}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070604153216/http://www.k12.dc.us/dcps/OFM/boundaries/boundaries.html District of Columbia Public Schools boundary maps]\n*[https://nonpartisaneducation.org/DCdocuments.htm Special Section: District of Columbia Public Education Documents: Agreements, Audits, Reports, Requests, etc., by Erich Martel]\n\n\n{{United States school districts}}\n{{District of Columbia}}\n{{NFHS}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:District Of Columbia Public Schools}}\n[[Category:District of Columbia Public Schools| ]]\n[[Category:School districts in the United States]]\n[[Category:Education in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Washington, D.C. education-related lists|Public Schools]]\n[[Category:1805 establishments in Washington, D.C.]]\n", "name_user": "Jspace727", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eElementary schools:Consolidated references", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/District_of_Columbia_Public_Schools"}
{"title_page": "TWA Flight 427", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{multiple issues|\n{{More footnotes|date=July 2009}}\n{{Refimprove|date=July 2009}}\n}}\n{{Infobox Aircraft accident\n|name = TWA Flight 427\n|date = November 22, 1994\n|type = [[Runway incursion]] due to [[pilot error]] of the Cessna<ref name=\"Final Report AAR-95-05\">{{cite book}} |url=http://libraryonline.erau.edu/online-full-text/ntsb/aircraft-accident-reports/AAR95-05.pdf |title=Aircraft Accident Report, Runway Collision Involving Trans World Airlines Flight 427 And Superior Aviation Cessna 441, Bridgeton, Missouri, November 22, 1994 |publisher=[[National Transportation Safety Board]] |date=August 30, 1995 |accessdate=August 24, 2016}}</ref>\n|occurrence_type = Accident\n|site = Bridgeton, Missouri\n|coordinates = {{coord|38|44|29|N|90|20|46|W|type:event|display=inline,title}}\n|total_fatalities  = 2\n|total_injuries    = 8 (minor)\n|total_survivors   = 140\n|plane1_image       = McDonnell Douglas MD-82 N954U 9054 Trans World Airlines, Boston - Logan International, USA, August 1990. (5619642079).jpg\n|plane1_caption     = N954U, seen at Logan International Airport, in August 1990\n|plane1_type       = [[McDonnell Douglas MD-80|McDonnell Douglas MD-82]]\n|plane1_operator   = [[Trans World Airlines]]\n|plane1_tailnum    = N954U\n|plane1_occupants = 140\n|plane1_passengers = 132\n|plane1_crew       = 8\n|plane1_injuries   = 8 (minor)\n|plane1_survivors  = 140\n|plane1_fatalities = 0\n|plane2_image       = File:Cessna 441 (5725693151).jpg\n|plane2_caption       = A Cessna 441, similar to the aircraft involved in the accident\n|plane2_type       = [[Cessna 441 Conquest II|Cessna 441]]\n|plane2_operator   = Superior Aviation\n|plane2_tailnum    = N441KM\n|plane2_occupants  = 2\n|plane2_passengers = 1\n|plane2_crew       = 1\n|plane2_injuries   = \n|plane2_survivors  = 0\n|plane2_fatalities = 2 \n}}\n\n'''TWA Flight 427''' was a regularly scheduled [[TWA]] passenger flight departing [[Lambert-St. Louis International Airport]] (STL) in [[Bridgeton, Missouri|Bridgeton]], [[Missouri]] on November 22, 1994, operated using a  [[McDonnell Douglas MD-80|McDonnell Douglas MD-82]].  On the takeoff roll it struck a [[Cessna 441 Conquest II]], killing both of its occupants.<ref name=\"FSF Vol53 No3\">{{cite web |url=https://flightsafety.org/ap/ap_mar96.pdf |title=Pilot of Cessna 441 Incorrectly Taxis onto Active Runway and Aircraft Is Struck by McDonnell Douglass MD-82 on Takeoff Roll |author=FSF Editorial Staff |publisher=[[Flight Safety Foundation]] |date=March 1996 |volume=53 |number=3 |accessdate=January 27, 2020}}</ref> It was the second of two flights numbered 427 that would be involved in an incident that year, the other being [[USAir Flight 427]], which crashed in September near [[Pittsburgh|Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania]] killing all 132 on board.\n\n==Aircraft==\nTWA Flight 427 was a regularly scheduled passenger flight from St. Louis International Airport to [[Stapleton International Airport]] in [[Denver]], [[Colorado]].<ref name=\"Final Report AAR-95-05\" />{{rp|1}}  On the date of the accident, Flight 427 was operated using a McDonnell Douglas MD-82 (registration number ''N954U'').<ref name=\"Final Report AAR-95-05\" />{{rp|1}}  There were 132 passengers and 8 crew on board.<ref name=\"Final Report AAR-95-05\" />{{rp|1}}  The captain of Flight 427 was Rick Carr, the first officer was Randy Speed, and Randy Richardson was an off-duty crew member occupying the cockpit jumpseat.\n\nOn November 22, 1994, Superior Aviation, Inc., a charter airline, operated a charter flight to St. Louis International Airport using a Cessna 441 Conquest II (registration number ''{{not a typo|N441KM}}'').<ref name=\"Final Report AAR-95-05\" />{{rp|1}}  After the charter passenger deplaned at St. Louis, the Cessna was then scheduled to depart St. Louis en route to another charter pickup.<ref name=\"Final Report AAR-95-05\" />{{rp|1\u20132}}\n\n==Accident==\nFlight 427 was scheduled to depart STL at 21:34 [[Central Standard Time]], but pushed back from the gate about 15 minutes late.  Apart from the delay, ground operations were routine.  Flight 427 was given instructions to taxi to Runway 30R.  At 22:01, the first officer advised local controllers that Flight 427 was ready for departure from Runway 30R.<ref name=\"Final Report AAR-95-05\" />{{rp|1}}\n\nThe Cessna arrived in STL and, at about 21:40, taxied to the charter aviation terminal to drop off its passenger.  At 21:58, the Cessna's pilot advised ground control that he was ready to taxi back to the runway for departure.  The ground controller instructed the Cessna to \"back-taxi into position\" and hold on Runway 31, and then advise the controller when in position for departure.<ref name=\"Final Report AAR-95-05\" />{{rp|2}} Although not a formally defined aviation term, \"back-taxiing\" generally referred to using a runway to taxi in a direction opposite the direction of departing or landing traffic, in order to reach the takeoff position.<ref name=\"Final Report AAR-95-05\" />{{rp|2,38}} Although the ground controller specifically stated Runway 31, the Cessna pilot did not repeat the runway number when acknowledging his instructions. After being cleared to back-taxi on Runway 31, the Cessna pilot instead taxied onto Runway 30R, which Flight 427 was preparing to depart from.<ref name=\"Final Report AAR-95-05\" />{{rp|47}}\n\nAt 22:01:23, Flight 427 was cleared for takeoff from Runway 30R, and the MD-82 taxied onto Runway 30R, with Speed at the controls.<ref name=\"Final Report AAR-95-05\" />{{rp|2}}  Flight 427 began accelerating down the runway at 22:02:27.<ref name=\"Final Report AAR-95-05\" />{{rp|109}}  Two seconds later, the Cessna's pilot advised the local controller that he was \"ready to go on the right side.\"<ref name=\"Final Report AAR-95-05\" />{{rp|2}}  At 22:02:40, Carr called out reaching an airspeed of 80 knots; 2-3 seconds later, Richardson yelled, \"There's an airplane!\"<ref name=\"Final Report AAR-95-05\" />{{rp|3,109}} At the same, both Speed and Carr saw the Cessna and applied braking, and Carr applied hard left rudder in an attempt to direct their aircraft around the Cessna.  About 2-3 seconds after they first saw the Cessna, the flight crew of Flight 427 felt the Cessna impact the right side of their plane.  Flight 427's flight crew aborted their takeoff, and brought the plane to a stop on the left side of Runway 30R.<ref name=\"Final Report AAR-95-05\" />{{rp|3}}\n\nThe right wing of the MD-82 tore horizontal and vertical stabilizers off the fuselage of the Cessna, and sheared off the top of the Cessna's fuselage and cockpit; both occupants of the Cessna were killed.<ref name=\"Final Report AAR-95-05\" />{{rp|3}} The MD-82's cockpit and cabin were not damaged, and no one on board the MD-82 was killed or injured in the collision. Carr shut down the MD-82's engines and immediately called for emergency vehicles.<ref name=\"Final Report AAR-95-05\" />{{rp|20}} Carr then asked the tower for help determining if there was a fire; the controller asserted he did not, then asserted that the Cessna was not supposed to be on Runway 30R, telling Carr, \"He was supposed to be on runway three one. I did not see the aircraft on that runway.\" Carr responded, \"All that later, I just want to make sure everything's safe here.\"<ref name=\"AP 1995 Pilot Kept Cool\">{{cite news |url=https://www.sfgate.com/news/article/FAA-Tapes-Show-Pilot-Kept-Cool-During-Fatal-Crash-3048143.php |title=FAA Tapes Show Pilot Kept Cool During Fatal Crash on Runway |publisher=[[Associated Press]] |date=January 14, 1995 |accessdate=January 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\nDue to a large amount of spilled [[jet fuel]], a fire hazard existed and an immediate evacuation was necessary.<ref name=\"Final Report AAR-95-05\" />{{rp|20}} Eight passengers sustained minor injuries in the evacuation of the aircraft.<ref name=\"Final Report AAR-95-05\" />{{rp|1}} The airport authority did not officially close the airport after the accident. Aircraft continued to land on runway 30L and taxi nearby during passenger evacuation.<ref name=\"Final Report AAR-95-05\" />{{rp|21}}\n\n==Investigation==\nThe resulting [[National Transportation Safety Board|NTSB]] investigation determined that the Cessna had recently flown in from [[Iron Mountain, Michigan|Iron Mountain]], [[Michigan]]. It had landed on runway 30R and dropped off a passenger before preparing for the return flight. A commercial-rated pilot and a pilot-rated passenger, married to an employee of Superior Aviation, were on board as it left the ramp.{{cn|date=January 2020}} The NTSB could not determine the reason the Cessna's pilot taxied onto the wrong runway, but considered multiple theories, including fatigue from the late hour and anxiety to beat deteriorating weather at the Cessna's destination. Ultimately, the NTSB concluded that the pilot likely had formed a preconceived notion that he would be using Runway 30R, which he had used on arrival, rather than Runway 31.<ref name=\"Final Report AAR-95-05\" />{{rp|47}}<ref name=\"FSF Vol53 No3\"/>{{rp|9}}\n\nThe [[Automatic Terminal Information Service|ATIS]] information broadcast to all pilots advised that runways 30L and 30R were in use for arrivals and departures. Although runway 31 was routinely used in these conditions for general-aviation aircraft, this information was not included on the hourly ATIS broadcast.<ref name=\"Final Report AAR-95-05\" />{{rp|47}} The NTSB believed that if the ATIS broadcasts mentioned Runway 31 as an active runway, the Cessna pilot might have been more attentive to the mention of Runway 31 in the ground controller's taxi instructions.<ref name=\"FSF Vol53 No3\"/>{{rp|9}} In addition, the NTSB criticized the ground controller's use of non-standard phrasing and failure to require the Cessna pilot to repeat back the runway he was cleared to.<ref name=\"Final Report AAR-95-05\" />{{rp|47}}<ref name=\"FSF Vol53 No3\"/>{{rp|9}}\n\nAccording to an NTSB spokesman, Flight 427's pilots averted a major disaster by pulling the aircraft to the left before impact, a maneuver that \"avoided what would have been a much worse accident.\"<ref name=\"AP 1995 Pilot Kept Cool\"/>\n\n==Aftermath==\nThe NTSB recommended pilots should be required to read back runway assignments and controllers verify readback.  In response, the FAA modified the air traffic controller's handbook to require that controllers obtain confirmation of runway assignment from pilots after issuing taxi instructions. The NTSB endorsed the FAA's action and expressed its view that had this procedure been in effect on the day of this accident, the accident might not have occurred.<ref name=\"FSF Vol53 No3\"/>{{rp|8\u20139}} The NTSB also recommend that the FAA formalize a definition of \"back-taxi\" so that its use could be standardized.<ref name=\"FSF Vol53 No3\"/>{{rp|9}}\n\nIn addition, the NTSB recommended that ground radar be installed at STL, and reiterated its standing recommendation that all airports should immediately close following any incident until the situation has been assessed.{{cn|date=January 2020}}\n\nAs of 2008, runway 13/31 has been converted into taxiway F. Taxiway R has been renamed to taxiway J and taxiway P is now taxiway E.{{cn|date=January 2020}}\n\n==References==\n{{NTSB}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{ASN accident|id=19941122-0}}\n\n{{Aviation incidents and accidents in 1994}}\n{{TWA}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:TWA Flight 427}}\n[[Category:1994 in Missouri]]\n[[Category:Airliner accidents and incidents in Missouri]]\n[[Category:Aviation accidents and incidents in the United States in 1994]]\n[[Category:Trans World Airlines accidents and incidents|427]]\n[[Category:Runway incursions]]\n[[Category:Disasters in Missouri]]\n[[Category:History of St. Louis County, Missouri]]\n[[Category:November 1994 events in the United States]]\n[[Category:St. Louis Lambert International Airport]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{multiple issues|\n{{More footnotes|date=July 2009}}\n{{Refimprove|date=July 2009}}\n}}\n{{Infobox Aircraft accident\n|name = TWA Flight 427\n|date = November 22, 1994\n|type = [[Runway incursion]] due to [[pilot error]]<ref name=\"Final Report AAR-95-05\">{{cite book |url=http://libraryonline.erau.edu/online-full-text/ntsb/aircraft-accident-reports/AAR95-05.pdf |title=Aircraft Accident Report, Runway Collision Involving Trans World Airlines Flight 427 And Superior Aviation Cessna 441, Bridgeton, Missouri, November 22, 1994 |publisher=[[National Transportation Safety Board]] |date=August 30, 1995 |accessdate=August 24, 2016}}</ref>\n|occurrence_type = Accident\n|site = Bridgeton, Missouri\n|coordinates = {{coord|38|44|29|N|90|20|46|W|type:event|display=inline,title}}\n|total_fatalities  = 2\n|total_injuries    = 8 (minor)\n|total_survivors   = 140\n|plane1_image       = McDonnell Douglas MD-82 N954U 9054 Trans World Airlines, Boston - Logan International, USA, August 1990. (5619642079).jpg\n|plane1_caption     = N954U, seen at Logan International Airport, in August 1990\n|plane1_type       = [[McDonnell Douglas MD-80|McDonnell Douglas MD-82]]\n|plane1_operator   = [[Trans World Airlines]]\n|plane1_tailnum    = N954U\n|plane1_occupants = 140\n|plane1_passengers = 132\n|plane1_crew       = 8\n|plane1_injuries   = 8 (minor)\n|plane1_survivors  = 140\n|plane1_fatalities = 0\n|plane2_image       = File:Cessna 441 (5725693151).jpg\n|plane2_caption       = A Cessna 441, similar to the aircraft involved in the accident\n|plane2_type       = [[Cessna 441 Conquest II|Cessna 441]]\n|plane2_operator   = Superior Aviation\n|plane2_tailnum    = N441KM\n|plane2_occupants  = 2\n|plane2_passengers = 1\n|plane2_crew       = 1\n|plane2_injuries   = \n|plane2_survivors  = 0\n|plane2_fatalities = 2 \n}}\n\n'''TWA Flight 427''' was a regularly scheduled [[TWA]] passenger flight departing [[Lambert-St. Louis International Airport]] (STL) in [[Bridgeton, Missouri|Bridgeton]], [[Missouri]] on November 22, 1994, operated using a  [[McDonnell Douglas MD-80|McDonnell Douglas MD-82]].  On the takeoff roll it struck a [[Cessna 441 Conquest II]], killing both of its occupants.<ref name=\"FSF Vol53 No3\">{{cite web |url=https://flightsafety.org/ap/ap_mar96.pdf |title=Pilot of Cessna 441 Incorrectly Taxis onto Active Runway and Aircraft Is Struck by McDonnell Douglass MD-82 on Takeoff Roll |author=FSF Editorial Staff |publisher=[[Flight Safety Foundation]] |date=March 1996 |volume=53 |number=3 |accessdate=January 27, 2020}}</ref> It was the second of two flights numbered 427 that would be involved in an incident that year, the other being [[USAir Flight 427]], which crashed in September near [[Pittsburgh|Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania]] killing all 132 on board.\n\n==Aircraft==\nTWA Flight 427 was a regularly scheduled passenger flight from St. Louis International Airport to [[Stapleton International Airport]] in [[Denver]], [[Colorado]].<ref name=\"Final Report AAR-95-05\" />{{rp|1}}  On the date of the accident, Flight 427 was operated using a McDonnell Douglas MD-82 (registration number ''N954U'').<ref name=\"Final Report AAR-95-05\" />{{rp|1}}  There were 132 passengers and 8 crew on board.<ref name=\"Final Report AAR-95-05\" />{{rp|1}}  The captain of Flight 427 was Rick Carr, the first officer was Randy Speed, and Randy Richardson was an off-duty crew member occupying the cockpit jumpseat.\n\nOn November 22, 1994, Superior Aviation, Inc., a charter airline, operated a charter flight to St. Louis International Airport using a Cessna 441 Conquest II (registration number ''{{not a typo|N441KM}}'').<ref name=\"Final Report AAR-95-05\" />{{rp|1}}  After the charter passenger deplaned at St. Louis, the Cessna was then scheduled to depart St. Louis en route to another charter pickup.<ref name=\"Final Report AAR-95-05\" />{{rp|1\u20132}}\n\n==Accident==\nFlight 427 was scheduled to depart STL at 21:34 [[Central Standard Time]], but pushed back from the gate about 15 minutes late.  Apart from the delay, ground operations were routine.  Flight 427 was given instructions to taxi to Runway 30R.  At 22:01, the first officer advised local controllers that Flight 427 was ready for departure from Runway 30R.<ref name=\"Final Report AAR-95-05\" />{{rp|1}}\n\nThe Cessna arrived in STL and, at about 21:40, taxied to the charter aviation terminal to drop off its passenger.  At 21:58, the Cessna's pilot advised ground control that he was ready to taxi back to the runway for departure.  The ground controller instructed the Cessna to \"back-taxi into position\" and hold on Runway 31, and then advise the controller when in position for departure.<ref name=\"Final Report AAR-95-05\" />{{rp|2}} Although not a formally defined aviation term, \"back-taxiing\" generally referred to using a runway to taxi in a direction opposite the direction of departing or landing traffic, in order to reach the takeoff position.<ref name=\"Final Report AAR-95-05\" />{{rp|2,38}} Although the ground controller specifically stated Runway 31, the Cessna pilot did not repeat the runway number when acknowledging his instructions. After being cleared to back-taxi on Runway 31, the Cessna pilot instead taxied onto Runway 30R, which Flight 427 was preparing to depart from.<ref name=\"Final Report AAR-95-05\" />{{rp|47}}\n\nAt 22:01:23, Flight 427 was cleared for takeoff from Runway 30R, and the MD-82 taxied onto Runway 30R, with Speed at the controls.<ref name=\"Final Report AAR-95-05\" />{{rp|2}}  Flight 427 began accelerating down the runway at 22:02:27.<ref name=\"Final Report AAR-95-05\" />{{rp|109}}  Two seconds later, the Cessna's pilot advised the local controller that he was \"ready to go on the right side.\"<ref name=\"Final Report AAR-95-05\" />{{rp|2}}  At 22:02:40, Carr called out reaching an airspeed of 80 knots; 2-3 seconds later, Richardson yelled, \"There's an airplane!\"<ref name=\"Final Report AAR-95-05\" />{{rp|3,109}} At the same, both Speed and Carr saw the Cessna and applied braking, and Carr applied hard left rudder in an attempt to direct their aircraft around the Cessna.  About 2-3 seconds after they first saw the Cessna, the flight crew of Flight 427 felt the Cessna impact the right side of their plane.  Flight 427's flight crew aborted their takeoff, and brought the plane to a stop on the left side of Runway 30R.<ref name=\"Final Report AAR-95-05\" />{{rp|3}}\n\nThe right wing of the MD-82 tore horizontal and vertical stabilizers off the fuselage of the Cessna, and sheared off the top of the Cessna's fuselage and cockpit; both occupants of the Cessna were killed.<ref name=\"Final Report AAR-95-05\" />{{rp|3}} The MD-82's cockpit and cabin were not damaged, and no one on board the MD-82 was killed or injured in the collision. Carr shut down the MD-82's engines and immediately called for emergency vehicles.<ref name=\"Final Report AAR-95-05\" />{{rp|20}} Carr then asked the tower for help determining if there was a fire; the controller asserted he did not, then asserted that the Cessna was not supposed to be on Runway 30R, telling Carr, \"He was supposed to be on runway three one. I did not see the aircraft on that runway.\" Carr responded, \"All that later, I just want to make sure everything's safe here.\"<ref name=\"AP 1995 Pilot Kept Cool\">{{cite news |url=https://www.sfgate.com/news/article/FAA-Tapes-Show-Pilot-Kept-Cool-During-Fatal-Crash-3048143.php |title=FAA Tapes Show Pilot Kept Cool During Fatal Crash on Runway |publisher=[[Associated Press]] |date=January 14, 1995 |accessdate=January 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\nDue to a large amount of spilled [[jet fuel]], a fire hazard existed and an immediate evacuation was necessary.<ref name=\"Final Report AAR-95-05\" />{{rp|20}} Eight passengers sustained minor injuries in the evacuation of the aircraft.<ref name=\"Final Report AAR-95-05\" />{{rp|1}} The airport authority did not officially close the airport after the accident. Aircraft continued to land on runway 30L and taxi nearby during passenger evacuation.<ref name=\"Final Report AAR-95-05\" />{{rp|21}}\n\n==Investigation==\nThe resulting [[National Transportation Safety Board|NTSB]] investigation determined that the Cessna had recently flown in from [[Iron Mountain, Michigan|Iron Mountain]], [[Michigan]]. It had landed on runway 30R and dropped off a passenger before preparing for the return flight. A commercial-rated pilot and a pilot-rated passenger, married to an employee of Superior Aviation, were on board as it left the ramp.{{cn|date=January 2020}} The NTSB could not determine the reason the Cessna's pilot taxied onto the wrong runway, but considered multiple theories, including fatigue from the late hour and anxiety to beat deteriorating weather at the Cessna's destination. Ultimately, the NTSB concluded that the pilot likely had formed a preconceived notion that he would be using Runway 30R, which he had used on arrival, rather than Runway 31.<ref name=\"Final Report AAR-95-05\" />{{rp|47}}<ref name=\"FSF Vol53 No3\"/>{{rp|9}}\n\nThe [[Automatic Terminal Information Service|ATIS]] information broadcast to all pilots advised that runways 30L and 30R were in use for arrivals and departures. Although runway 31 was routinely used in these conditions for general-aviation aircraft, this information was not included on the hourly ATIS broadcast.<ref name=\"Final Report AAR-95-05\" />{{rp|47}} The NTSB believed that if the ATIS broadcasts mentioned Runway 31 as an active runway, the Cessna pilot might have been more attentive to the mention of Runway 31 in the ground controller's taxi instructions.<ref name=\"FSF Vol53 No3\"/>{{rp|9}} In addition, the NTSB criticized the ground controller's use of non-standard phrasing and failure to require the Cessna pilot to repeat back the runway he was cleared to.<ref name=\"Final Report AAR-95-05\" />{{rp|47}}<ref name=\"FSF Vol53 No3\"/>{{rp|9}}\n\nAccording to an NTSB spokesman, Flight 427's pilots averted a major disaster by pulling the aircraft to the left before impact, a maneuver that \"avoided what would have been a much worse accident.\"<ref name=\"AP 1995 Pilot Kept Cool\"/>\n\n==Aftermath==\nThe NTSB recommended pilots should be required to read back runway assignments and controllers verify readback.  In response, the FAA modified the air traffic controller's handbook to require that controllers obtain confirmation of runway assignment from pilots after issuing taxi instructions. The NTSB endorsed the FAA's action and expressed its view that had this procedure been in effect on the day of this accident, the accident might not have occurred.<ref name=\"FSF Vol53 No3\"/>{{rp|8\u20139}} The NTSB also recommend that the FAA formalize a definition of \"back-taxi\" so that its use could be standardized.<ref name=\"FSF Vol53 No3\"/>{{rp|9}}\n\nIn addition, the NTSB recommended that ground radar be installed at STL, and reiterated its standing recommendation that all airports should immediately close following any incident until the situation has been assessed.{{cn|date=January 2020}}\n\nAs of 2008, runway 13/31 has been converted into taxiway F. Taxiway R has been renamed to taxiway J and taxiway P is now taxiway E.{{cn|date=January 2020}}\n\n==References==\n{{NTSB}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{ASN accident|id=19941122-0}}\n\n{{Aviation incidents and accidents in 1994}}\n{{TWA}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:TWA Flight 427}}\n[[Category:1994 in Missouri]]\n[[Category:Airliner accidents and incidents in Missouri]]\n[[Category:Aviation accidents and incidents in the United States in 1994]]\n[[Category:Trans World Airlines accidents and incidents|427]]\n[[Category:Runway incursions]]\n[[Category:Disasters in Missouri]]\n[[Category:History of St. Louis County, Missouri]]\n[[Category:November 1994 events in the United States]]\n[[Category:St. Louis Lambert International Airport]]\n", "name_user": "Why can't I edit Userpedia?", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/TWA_Flight_427"}
